# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: clutch-hitter
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The **2001 World Series** was the championship series of Major League Baseball's (MLB) 2001 season.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The 97th edition of the World Series, it was a best-of-seven series between the National League (NL) champion Arizona Diamondbacks and the American League (AL) champion (and three-time defending World Series champion) New York Yankees.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Diamondbacks defeated the Yankees, four games to three, to win the series.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Considered one of the greatest World Series of all time, its memorable aspects included two extra-inning games and three late-inning comebacks.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Diamondbacks pitchers Randy Johnson and Curt Schilling were both named World Series Most Valuable Players.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Yankees advanced to the World Series by defeating the Oakland Athletics, three games to two, in the AL Division Series, and then the Seattle Mariners in the AL Championship Series, four games to one.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] It was the Yankees' fourth consecutive World Series appearance, after winning championships in 1998, 1999, and 2000.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Diamondbacks advanced to the World Series by defeating the St.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Louis Cardinals, three games to two, in the NL Division Series, and then the Atlanta Braves in the NL Championship Series, four games to one.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] It was the franchise's first appearance in a World Series.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Series began later than usual, as a result of a delay in the regular season after the September 11 attacks, and it was the first to extend into November.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Diamondbacks won the first two games at home, limiting the Yankees to just one run.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Yankees responded with a close win in Game 3, at which U.S.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Bush threw out the ceremonial first pitch.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] In Games 4 and 5, the Yankees won in comeback fashion, hitting game-tying home runs off Diamondbacks closer Byung-hyun Kim with one out remaining in consecutive games, before winning in extra innings.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Diamondbacks won Game 6 in a blowout, forcing a decisive Game 7.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] In the final game, the Yankees led in the ninth inning before the Diamondbacks staged a comeback against closer Mariano Rivera, capped off by a walk-off, bases-loaded bloop single by Luis Gonzalez to clinch Arizona's championship victory.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] This was the third World Series to end in a bases-loaded, walk-off hit, following 1991 and 1997, and to this date, the last Series to end on a walk-off of any kind.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] This series held the record for the latest date that a Series ended (November 4), until that record was broken during the 2022 World Series.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The home team won every game in the Series, which had only happened twice before, in 1987 and 1991, both won by the Minnesota Twins.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Diamondbacks outscored the Yankees, 37–14, as a result of large margins of victory achieved by Arizona at Bank One Ballpark (now known as Chase Field) relative to the one-run margins the Yankees achieved at Yankee Stadium.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Arizona's pitching held powerhouse New York to a .183 batting average, the lowest ever in a seven-game World Series.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] This and the 2002 World Series were the last two consecutive World Series to have game sevens until the World Series of 2016 and 2017, and the last two consecutive ones where Game 7 was won by the home team.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The 2001 World Series was the subject of an HBO documentary, *Nine Innings from Ground Zero*, in 2004.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Arizona Diamondbacks began play in 1998, along with the Tampa Bay Devil Rays, as the youngest expansion team in Major League Baseball (MLB).
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] After a mediocre debut season, the Diamondbacks finished the following year first in the National League (NL) West with a 100–62 record, but lost to the New York Mets in the National League Division series.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] With several All-Star players like Randy Johnson and Matt Williams, the Diamondbacks had high expectations for the 2000 season, but finished third in the NL West with an 85–77 record.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] During the offseason, team manager Buck Showalter was fired, and replaced by sportscaster Bob Brenly.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Diamondbacks acquired several notable free agent players during the offseason, including Miguel Batista, Mark Grace, and Reggie Sanders.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Most of the Diamondbacks players were above the age of 30, and had already played on a number of teams prior to the 2001 season.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] In fact, the Diamondbacks starting lineup for the World Series did not include a player under the age of 31, making them the oldest team by player age in World Series history.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] With several players nearing the age of retirement, Luis Gonzalez noted that the overall team mentality was "there's too many good guys in here to let this opportunity slip away".
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Although the Diamondbacks were only one game above .500 by the end of April, Gonzalez had a particularly memorable start to the season, in which he tied the MLB record with 13 home runs during the month of April.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Diamondbacks found greater success in May and June, and at one point had a six-game lead in the NL West.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] During this span, the team won nine consecutive games, and Johnson tied the MLB record with 20 strikeouts in a nine-inning game.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The six game lead did not last long however, and by the end of July, the Diamondbacks were a half game behind the Los Angeles Dodgers in the West.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] A resurgent August pushed the team back into first place, a spot they maintained for the rest of the season.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] By the end of the season, several Diamondbacks players had put up exceptional statistics: Curt Schilling had the most wins of any pitcher in MLB that year with 22, while Johnson nearly broke the single season strikeout record with 372.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Johnson and Schilling also had the two lowest earned run averages (ERA) in the NL, with 2.49 and 2.98 respectively.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Gonzalez ended the season with a .325 batting average and 57 home runs, and finished third in voting for the NL Most Valuable Player Award.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Diamondbacks were also one of the best defensive teams in MLB that year, second in fewest errors committed, and tied with the Seattle Mariners for the best fielding percentage.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Diamondbacks entered the postseason as the #2 seed in the National League, and played the #4 seed St.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Louis Cardinals in the National League Division Series.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Schilling threw a shutout in Game 1 to give the Diamondbacks an early series lead, but the Cardinals won Game 2 thanks to a two-run home run from Albert Pujols.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Craig Counsell hit a three-run home run late in Game 3 to give the Diamondbacks a 2–1 series lead, but the Cardinals won Game 4 with strong pitching performances from Bud Smith and their relief pitchers.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Diamondbacks clinched the series in Game 5, when Tony Womack hit a game winning single that scored Danny Bautista.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] They then faced the third seeded Atlanta Braves in the National League Championship Series.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Johnson also threw a shutout in Game 1, while the Braves hit three home runs in Game 2 to tie the series at one game apiece.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Schilling threw a complete game in Game 3, and the Diamondbacks scored 11 runs in a Game 4 victory to take a 3–1 series lead.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Diamondbacks clinched the series in Game 5 with another strong performance from Johnson.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] With the win, they became the fastest expansion team to reach the World Series, in just their fourth year of play.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] In contrast to the Diamondbacks, the New York Yankees were one of the oldest and most recognized teams in all of North American sports.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Yankees had built a dynasty in the late 1990s that extended into 2000, which included winning three consecutive World Series' and four of the last five.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] These teams were led by a group of talented young players that became known as the Core Four: Derek Jeter, Andy Pettitte, Jorge Posada, and Mariano Rivera.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Yankees finished the 2001 season in first place in the AL East with a win–loss record of 95–65 (a winning percentage of .594), 13+1⁄2 games ahead of the Boston Red Sox, good enough to secure the #2 seed in the American League playoff bracket.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Yankees then defeated the fourth seeded Oakland Athletics 3 games to 2 in the AL Division Series, after losing 2 games at home, and the top seeded Seattle Mariners 4 games to 1 in the AL Championship Series to advance to their fourth consecutive World Series, and fifth in six years.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Derek Jeter and Tino Martinez led the Yankees offensively during the 2001 season.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Jeter batted .311 with 21 home runs and 74 RBI in 150 games, while Martinez batted .280 with 34 home runs and 113 RBI in 154 games.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Roger Clemens and Mike Mussina were the leaders of the Yankees' pitching staff.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Clemens who won the Cy Young Award, his sixth of a career total and major league record 7, finished with a win–loss record of 20–3, an earned-run average (ERA) of 3.51, and struck out 213 batters in 220.1 innings pitched and was by far the Yankee's best starter in the World Series.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Mussina finished with a win–loss record of 17–11, an ERA of 3.15, and struck out 214 batters in 228.2 innings pitched.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] After MLB games were postponed as a result of the September 11 attacks, the World Series began on October 27, 2001, which was, at the time, the latest-ever start date for a World Series.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The last three games were the first major-league games (other than exhibitions) played in the month of November.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] This was just the fourth time that no World Series champion was decided within the traditional month of October.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The previous three occurrences were in 1904 (no series), 1918 (series held in September because of World War I), and 1994 (series cancelled by the players' strike).
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Game 7 was played on November 4; at the time this was the latest date a World Series game was played, and still tied with Game 6 of the 2009 Series for the second-latest date of a World Series game (only behind 2022's Game 6, played on November 5).
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Additionally, the Series took place in New York City only seven weeks after the attacks, representing a remarkable boost in morale for the fatigued city.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] A tattered and torn American flag recovered from the wreckage at Ground Zero, which had been used at funerals of fallen Port Authority police officers after the attacks, was flown over Yankee Stadium during the series.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Bush threw out the ceremonial first pitch before Game 3 at Yankee Stadium.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Bush had been counseled by security officials to appear before Game 1 in Phoenix because they believed it would be more secure there, but Bush thought it would be better for the country to do it in New York.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Security was extremely tight at Yankee Stadium before the game, with bomb sniffing dogs sweeping the property, snipers positioned around the stadium, and vendors screened by federal agents.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] A Secret Service agent dressed as an umpire and stood on the field with the other umpires before the game, briefly appearing on the TV broadcast.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Bush wore a bulletproof vest underneath an FDNY sweater.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Having been counseled by Derek Jeter to throw from the rubber on top of the pitcher's mound rather than the base of the mound, Bush strode to the rubber, gave a thumbs up to the crowd, and fired a strike over home plate as the crowd chanted "U-S-A".
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Bush later reflected, "I had never had such an adrenaline rush as when I finally made it to the mound.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] I was saying to the crowd, 'I'm with you, the country's with you' ...
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Series commenced on October 27, which was the latest a World Series had started, beating the previous record by four days (1999 World Series, October 23).
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Yankees struck first in Game 1 when Derek Jeter was hit by a pitch with one out in the first and scored on Bernie Williams's double two batters later.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] However, Arizona's Curt Schilling and two relievers, Mike Morgan and Greg Swindell held the Yankees scoreless afterward.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] They managed to get only two walks and two hits for the rest of the game, Scott Brosius's double in the second and Jorge Posada's single in the fourth, both with two outs.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Meanwhile, the Diamondbacks tied the game on Craig Counsell's one-out home run in the first off of Mike Mussina.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] After a scoreless second, Mussina led off the third by hitting Tony Womack with a pitch.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] He moved to second on Counsell's sacrifice bunt before Luis Gonzalez's home run put the Diamondbacks up 3–1.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] A single and right fielder David Justice's error put runners on second and third before Matt Williams's sacrifice fly put Arizona up 4–1.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] After Mark Grace was intentionally walked, Damian Miller's RBI double gave Arizona a 5–1 lead.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Next inning, Gonzalez hit a two-out double off of Randy Choate.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Reggie Sanders was intentionally walked before Gonzalez scored on Steve Finley's single.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] An error by third baseman Brosius scored Sanders, put Finley at third, and Williams at second.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Both men scored on Mark Grace's double, putting Arizona up 9–1.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Though the Diamondbacks got just one more hit for the rest of the game off of Sterling Hitchcock and Mike Stanton (Williams' leadoff single in the seventh), they went up 1–0 in the series.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Diamondbacks' win in Game 1 was the first World Series game won by a non-New York City team since 1997.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] In every World Series between 1997 and 2001, either both teams were from New York City or a New York City team won in a sweep (1998 and 1999).
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Arizona continued to take control of the Series with the strong pitching performance of Randy Johnson.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Big Unit pitched a complete-game shutout, allowing only four baserunners and three hits while striking out 11 Yankees.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Andy Pettitte meanwhile nearly matched him, retiring Arizona in order in five of the seven innings he pitched.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] In the second, he allowed a leadoff single to Reggie Sanders, who scored on Danny Bautista's double.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Bautista was the only Arizona runner stranded for the entire game.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] In the seventh, Pettitte hit Luis Gonzalez with a pitch before Sanders grounded into a forceout.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] After Bautista singled, Matt Williams's three-run home run put Arizona up 4–0.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] They won the game with that score and led the series two games to none as it moved to New York City.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] This was the 1,000th game played in the history of the MLB postseason.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The game was opened in New York City by President George W.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Bush, who threw the ceremonial first pitch, a strike to Yankees backup catcher Todd Greene.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Bush became the first incumbent U.S. president to throw a World Series first pitch since Jimmy Carter in 1979.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] He also threw the baseball from the mound where the pitcher would be set (unlike most ceremonial first pitches which are from in front of the mound) and threw it for a strike.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Chants of *"U-S-A, U-S-A"* rang throughout Yankee Stadium.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Yankees starter Roger Clemens was outstanding allowing only three hits and struck out nine in seven innings of work.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Yankees closer Mariano Rivera pitched two innings for the save.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Jorge Posada's leadoff home run off of Brian Anderson in the second put the Yankees up 1–0.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Diamondbacks loaded the bases in the fourth on two walks and one hit before Matt Williams's sacrifice fly tied the game.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Bernie Williams hit a leadoff single in the sixth and moved to second on a wild pitch one out later before Posada walked.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Mike Morgan relieved Anderson and struck out David Justice before Scott Brosius broke the tie with an RBI single.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] That would be all the scoring as Morgan and Greg Swindell pitched the rest of the game for the Diamondbacks while Clemens and Rivera shut down the D'Backs.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Yankees cut Arizona's series lead to 2–1 with the win.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Game 4 saw the Yankees send Orlando Hernández to the mound while the Diamondbacks elected to bring back Curt Schilling on three days' rest.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Both pitchers gave up home runs, with Schilling doing so to Shane Spencer in the third inning and Hernandez doing so to Mark Grace in the fourth.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Hernandez pitched 6+1⁄3 solid innings, giving up four hits while Schilling went seven innings and gave up one.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] With the game still tied entering the eighth, Arizona struck.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] After Mike Stanton recorded the first out of the inning, Luis Gonzalez singled and Erubiel Durazo hit a double to bring him in.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Matt Williams followed by grounding into a fielder's choice off of Ramiro Mendoza, which scored pinch runner Midre Cummings and gave the team a 3–1 lead.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] With his team on the verge of taking a commanding 3–1 series lead, Diamondbacks manager Bob Brenly elected to bring in closer Byung-hyun Kim in the bottom of the eighth for a two-inning save.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Kim, at 22, became the first Korean-born player to play in the MLB World Series.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Kim struck out the side in the eighth, but ran into trouble in the ninth.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Derek Jeter led off by trying to bunt for a hit but was thrown out by Williams.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Paul O'Neill then lined a single in front of Gonzalez.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] After Bernie Williams struck out, Kim seemed to be out of trouble with Tino Martinez coming to the plate.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] However, Martinez drove the first pitch he saw from Kim into the right-center field bleachers, tying the score at 3–3.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Yankees were not done, as Jorge Posada walked and David Justice moved him into scoring position with a single.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Kim struck Spencer out to end the threat.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] When the scoreboard clock in Yankee Stadium passed midnight, World Series play in November began, with the message on the scoreboard "Welcome to November Baseball".
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Mariano Rivera took the hill for the Yankees in the tenth and retired the Diamondbacks in order.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Kim went out for a third inning of work and retired Scott Brosius and Alfonso Soriano, but Jeter hit an opposite field home run on a 3–2 pitch count from Kim.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] This home run gave the Yankees a 4–3 victory and tied the Series at two games apiece which guaranteed a return trip to Arizona and made Jeter the first player to hit a November home run and earning him the tongue-in-cheek nickname of "Mr.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Game 5 saw the Yankees return to Mike Mussina for the start while the Diamondbacks sent Miguel Batista, who had not pitched in twelve days, to the mound.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Batista pitched a strong 7+2⁄3 scoreless innings, striking out six, and reliever Greg Swindell got the last out of the eighth inning.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Mussina bounced back from his poor Game 1 start, recording ten strikeouts, but allowed solo home runs in the fifth inning to Steve Finley and Rod Barajas.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] In the top of the ninth, the soon to be retired Paul O'Neill was honored by Yankee fans who chanted his name to which O'Neill, who was visibly in tears, tipped his hat.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] With the Diamondbacks leading 2–0 in the ninth, Byung-hyun Kim was called upon for the save despite having thrown three innings the night before.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Jorge Posada doubled to open the inning, but Kim got Shane Spencer to ground out and then struck out Chuck Knoblauch.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] As had happened the previous night, Kim could not hold the lead as Scott Brosius hit a 1–0 pitch over the left field wall, the second straight game tying home run in the bottom of the ninth for the Yankees.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Kim was pulled from the game in favor of Mike Morgan who recorded the final out.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Morgan retired the Yankees in order in the 10th and 11th innings, while the Diamondbacks got to Mariano Rivera in the 11th.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Danny Bautista and Erubiel Durazo opened the inning with hits and Matt Williams advanced them into scoring position with a sacrifice bunt.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Rivera then intentionally walked Steve Finley to load the bases, then got Reggie Sanders to line out and Mark Grace grounded out to end the inning.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Arizona went to midseason trade acquisition Albie Lopez in the 12th, and in his first at bat he gave up a single to Knoblauch (who had entered the game as a pinch runner).
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Brosius moved him over with a bunt, and then Alfonso Soriano ended the game with an RBI single to give the Yankees a 3–2 victory and a 3–2 series lead as the series went back to Phoenix.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Lopez would not pitch again in the series.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Sterling Hitchcock got the win for the Yankees after he relieved Rivera for the twelfth.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] With Arizona in a must-win situation, Randy Johnson pitched seven innings and struck out seven, giving up just two runs, and Bobby Witt and Troy Brohawn finished the blowout.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Diamondbacks struck first when Tony Womack hit a leadoff double off of Andy Pettitte and scored on Danny Bautista's single in the first.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Next inning, Womack's bases-loaded single scored two and Bautista's single scored another.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Yankees loaded the bases in the third on a single and two walks, but Johnson struck out Jorge Posada to end the inning.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Diamondbacks broke the game open with eight runs in the bottom half.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Pettitte allowed a leadoff walk to Greg Colbrunn and subsequent double to Matt Williams before being relieved by Jay Witasick, who allowed four straight singles to Reggie Sanders, Jay Bell, Damian Miller, and Johnson that scored three runs.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] After Womack struck out, Bautista's single scored two more runs and Luis Gonzalez's double scored another, with Bautista being thrown out at home.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Colbrunn's single and Williams's double scored a run each before Sanders struck out to end the inning.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] In the fourth, Bell reached first on a strike-three wild pitch before scoring on Miller's double.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Johnson struck out before Womack singled to knock Witasick out of the game.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] With Randy Choate pitching, Yankees second baseman Alfonso Soriano's error on Bautista's ground ball allowed Miller to score and put runners on first and second before Gonzalez's single scored the Diamondbacks' final run.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Choate and Mike Stanton kept them scoreless for the rest of the game.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Pettitte was charged with six runs in two innings while Witasick was charged with nine runs in 1+1⁄3 innings, the most runs allowed by any pitcher in a World Series game since Hall of Famer Walter Johnson also allowed nine runs in Game 7 of the 1925 World Series.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Yankees scored their only runs in the sixth on back-to-back one-out singles by Shane Spencer and Luis Sojo with runners on second and third, but by then the score had become so far out of reach that it didn't do the Yankees much good.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Diamondbacks hit six doubles and Danny Bautista batted 3-for-4 with five RBIs.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The team set a World Series record with 22 hits and defeated the New York Yankees in its most lopsided postseason loss in 293 postseason games, since surpassed by a 16–1 loss to the Boston Red Sox in Game 3 of the 2018 American League Division Series.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The 15–2 win evened the series at three games apiece and set up a Game 7 for the ages between Roger Clemens and Curt Schilling.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Diamondbacks’ thirteen-run margin of victory in Game 6 was the largest in a World Series game since Game 6 of the 1982 World Series, and is tied for the second largest margin of victory in a World Series game overall.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] to give the state of Arizona its first professional sports championship.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] It was a matchup of two 20-game winners in the Series finale.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Roger Clemens, at 39 years old, became the oldest Game 7 starter.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Curt Schilling had already started two games of the Series and pitched his 300th inning of the season on just three days' rest.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The two aces matched each other inning by inning and after seven full innings, the game was tied at 1–1.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Diamondbacks scored first in the sixth inning with a Steve Finley single and a Danny Bautista double (Bautista, trying to stretch it into a triple, was called out at third base).
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Yankees responded with an RBI single from Tino Martinez, which drove in Derek Jeter who had singled earlier.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Brenly stayed with Schilling into the eighth, and the move backfired as Alfonso Soriano hit a home run on an 0–2 pitch.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] After Schilling struck out Scott Brosius (who, like O'Neill, would also retire following the series), he gave up a single to David Justice, and he left the game trailing 2–1.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] With the Yankees ahead 2–1 in the bottom of the eighth, manager Joe Torre decided to relieve setup man Mike Stanton, who had got the last two outs, to his ace closer Mariano Rivera for a two-inning save.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Rivera struck out the side in the eighth, including Arizona's Luis Gonzalez, Matt Williams, and Bautista.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Although he was effective in the eighth, this game would end in the third ninth-inning comeback of the Series.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Mark Grace led off the inning with a single to center on a 1–0 pitch.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Rivera's errant throw to second base on a bunt attempt by catcher Damian Miller on an 0–1 pitch put runners on first and second.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Jeter tried to reach for the ball, but got tangled in the legs of pinch-runner David Dellucci, who was sliding in an attempt to break up the double play.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] During the next at bat, Rivera appeared to regain control when he fielded pinch hitter Jay Bell's (who was hitting for Johnson) bunt and threw out Dellucci at third base, but third baseman Brosius decided to hold onto the baseball instead of throwing to first to complete the double play.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Midre Cummings was sent in to pinch-run for Damian Miller, who had reached second base safely.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] With Cummings at second and Bell at first, the next batter, Womack, hit a double down the right-field line on a 2–2 pitch that tied the game and earned Rivera a blown save, his first in a postseason since 1997.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Bell advanced to third and the Yankees pulled the infield and outfield in as the potential winning run (Bell) stood at third with fewer than two outs.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] After Rivera hit Craig Counsell unintentionally with an 0–1 pitch, the bases were loaded.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] On an 0–1 pitch, with Williams in the on-deck circle, Gonzalez lofted a soft floater single over the drawn-in Jeter that barely reached the outfield grass, plating Jay Bell with the winning run.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] It was also the first, and remains the only, major professional sports championship won by a Phoenix-based team.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] As a result of the Diamondbacks’ victory, Randy Johnson became the first pitcher to win three World Series games since Mickey Lolich did so in 1968, and was the last to do so until Yoshinobu Yamamoto in 2025, though like Yamamoto, Johnson pitched fewer innings and only got his third win in relief.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Rivera took the loss, his only postseason loss in his career.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Coincidentally, this was also the second World Series in a 5-year span (1997 to 2001) to end with a game-winning RBI single.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Edgar Renteria hit the game-winner in the 1997 series, while Gonzalez hit it here, with Craig Counsell being on the basepaths for each.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] No other World Series has ended with a game-winning hit since 2001.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Two of the Diamondbacks' at-bats in the bottom of the 9th were rare "golden pitch" situations, by which either team could theoretically have won the World Series on the next pitch.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Mariano Rivera threw six pitches to Jay Bell (who bunted into a forceout on the first pitch) and Tony Womack (who hit an RBI double on the fifth pitch of the at-bat) during the 10th and 11th golden-pitch plate appearances in baseball history.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] In 2009, Game 7 of the 2001 World Series was chosen by *Sports Illustrated* as the Best Postseason Game of the Decade (2000–2009).
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] In the years that have followed, many fans (regardless of team allegiance) consider Game 7 of the 2001 World Series to be one of the greatest games ever played in the history of professional baseball.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] For the second consecutive year, Fox carried the World Series with its top broadcast team, Joe Buck and Tim McCarver (himself a Yankees broadcaster).
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] This was the first year of Fox's exclusive rights to the World Series (in the previous contract, Fox only broadcast the World Series in even numbered years while NBC broadcast it in odd numbered years), which it has held since.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] ESPN Radio provided national radio coverage for the fourth consecutive year, with Jon Miller and Joe Morgan calling the action.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Locally, the Series was broadcast by KTAR-AM in Phoenix with Thom Brennaman, Greg Schulte, Rod Allen and Jim Traber, and by WABC-AM in New York City with John Sterling and Michael Kay.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] This was WABC's last broadcast of Yankees baseball after twenty-one seasons as the team's flagship, and also the last time Sterling and Kay broadcast together after ten seasons.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Sterling and the Yankees joined WCBS-AM the next season on the radio side, while Kay was promoted to television as the YES Network launched for 2002.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Buster Olney, who covered the Yankees for *The New York Times* before joining ESPN, would write a book titled *The Last Night of the Yankee Dynasty*, published in 2004.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The book is a play by play account of Game 7 in addition to stories about key players, executives, and moments from the 1996–2001 dynasty.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] In a 2005 reprinting, Olney included a new epilogue covering the aftermath of the 2001 World Series up to the Boston Red Sox epic comeback from down 3–0 in the 2004 ALCS.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The official MLB Productions documentary film of the series was released in 2001.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] In 2004, HBO released *Nine Innings from Ground Zero*, a documentary focusing on the special role that baseball, and particularly the Yankees, played in helping to heal New York after 9/11.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The film features interviews with players, fans who lost family members, firefighters, sportswriters, and then United States President George W.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] In 2005, A&E Home Video released the *New York Yankees Fall Classic Collectors Edition (1996–2001)* DVD set.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Game 4 of the 2001 World Series is included in the set.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] In 2008, *The Arizona Diamondbacks 2001 World Series* DVD set was released.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] All seven games are included on this set.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Mariano Rivera, even in 2001, was considered the greatest closer ever.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Entering the bottom of the 9th inning, the deck was stacked against the Diamondbacks.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Rivera had a 0.70 career postseason ERA in 51 appearances.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] He once pitched a record 34 1/3 scoreless innings in the postseason and he had converted 23 consecutive save chances in the playoffs since Sandy Alomar's home run in Game 4 of the 1997 Division Series.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] However, it was the throwing error on Rivera's part that turned what could have been a save and Yankees fourth straight World Series into one of the most memorable moments in MLB history.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] "That's baseball," Rivera said after the game.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The duo of Curt Schilling and Randy Johnson were awarded the World Series Most Valuable Player, the first players to split the award since 1981, when Dodgers players Steve Yeager, Ron Cey, and Pedro Guerrero were declared co-winners, and last to do so, to date.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] This would not be the only award they split, as both were named Sports Illustrated Sportsperson of the Year for 2001.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Rivera's blown save and the Yankees' loss proved to be life-saving for Yankees utility player Enrique Wilson.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Had the Yankees won, Wilson was planning to fly home to the Dominican Republic for the winter on American Airlines Flight 587 on November 12 after what would have been a Yankees victory parade down the Canyon of Heroes.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] But after the Yankees lost (and thus no parade occurred), Wilson decided to fly home earlier.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Flight 587 would crash in Belle Harbor, Queens, killing everyone on board.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] During the offseason, several Yankees moved on to other teams or retired, the most notable changes being the free agent departures of Martinez and Knoblauch to the St.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Louis Cardinals and Kansas City Royals, and Brosius and O'Neill retiring.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Martinez would later return to the Yankees to finish his career in 2005.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] After winning the NL West again in 2002 the Diamondbacks were swept 3–0 by St.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] From here they declined, losing 111 games in 2004 as Bob Brenly was fired during that season.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Arizona would not win another NL West title until 2007.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Schilling was traded to the Boston Red Sox after the 2003 season and in 2004 helped lead them to their first World Series championship since 1918.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] He helped them win another championship in 2007 and retired after four years with Boston, missing the entire 2008 season with a shoulder injury.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Johnson was traded to the Yankees after the 2004 season, a season that saw him throw a perfect game against the Atlanta Braves, though he would be traded back to the Diamondbacks two years later and finish his career with the San Francisco Giants in 2009.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The last player from the 2001 Diamondbacks roster, Lyle Overbay, retired following the 2014 season with the Milwaukee Brewers while the last player from the 2001 Yankees, Randy Choate, retired following the 2016 season.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] In addition, including the World Series loss in 2001, every World Series champion from 2001 to 2004 won the title at the Yankees' expense in postseason play, which is an AL record and as of 2023 tied for the MLB record with the Los Angeles Dodgers from 2016 to 2019.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] Joe Torre's contract was allowed to expire and he was replaced by Joe Girardi in 2008, a season in which the Yankees would miss the playoffs for the first time since 1993.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Yankees would finally return to the World Series in 2024 only to fall in five games to the Los Angeles Dodgers.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] This remains the only championship among the four major North American men's professional sports won by a Phoenix-based team.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The NBA’s Phoenix Suns would make the NBA Finals three times in their history (1976, 1993, 2021), but lost all three in six games.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The NFL’s Arizona Cardinals made the Super Bowl in 2009, but narrowly lost to the Pittsburgh Steelers.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The NHL’s Arizona Coyotes never made the Stanley Cup Final and would later move to Salt Lake City, Utah to become the Utah Mammoth.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] However, the WNBA's Phoenix Mercury have won three championships since then (2007, 2009, and 2014).
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Diamondbacks and the Baltimore Ravens, who won the Super Bowl earlier in 2001, created the first instance of two major sports teams winning a championship game or series on their first attempts.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] This would not occur again until 2019, when two first time attempt champions won: the Toronto Raptors and Washington Nationals.
[src:clutch-hitter/2001-world-series] The Diamondbacks would not return to the World Series again until 2023; this time, they would go on to lose to the Texas Rangers in five games.
[src:clutch-hitter/ace-baseball] In baseball, an **ace** is a starting pitcher considered the best pitcher on a team's starting rotation.
[src:clutch-hitter/ace-baseball] Barring injury or exceptional circumstances, a team's ace typically starts on Opening Day.
[src:clutch-hitter/ace-baseball] In addition, aces are usually preferred to start crucial playoff games, sometimes on three days' rest.
[src:clutch-hitter/ace-baseball] The term may be a derivation of the nickname of Asa Brainard (real first name: "Asahel"), a 19th-century star pitcher, who was sometimes referred to as "Ace".
[src:clutch-hitter/ace-baseball] In the early days of baseball, the term *ace* was used to refer to a run.
[src:clutch-hitter/ace-baseball] Modern baseball analysts and fans have started using the term *ace* to refer to the elite pitchers in the game, not necessarily to the best starting pitcher on each team.
[src:clutch-hitter/ace-baseball] For example, the April 27, 1981, *Sports Illustrated* cover was captioned "The Amazing A's and Their Five Aces" to describe the starting rotation of the 1981 Oakland Athletics, which featured Mike Norris, Rick Langford, Matt Keough, Steve McCatty, and Brian Kingman.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] With a career .295 batting average, Rodriguez amassed over 600 home runs (696), over 2,000 runs batted in (RBI), over 2,000 runs scored, over 3,000 hits, and over 300 stolen bases, the only player in MLB history to achieve all of those feats.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] He was also a 14-time All-Star, winning three American League (AL) Most Valuable Player (MVP) Awards, ten Silver Slugger Awards, and two Gold Glove Awards.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] Rodriguez is also the career record holder for grand slams.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] During the 2000s decade, Rodriguez led all players in home runs (435), runs batted in (1,243), runs scored (1,190), and total bases (3,362).
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] The Mariners selected Rodriguez first overall in the 1993 MLB draft, and he debuted in the major leagues the following year at the age of 18.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] In 1996, he became the Mariners' starting shortstop, won the major league batting title, and finished second in voting for the AL MVP Award.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] His combination of power, speed, and defense made him a cornerstone of the franchise, but he left the team via free agency after the 2000 season to join the Rangers.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] The 10-year, $252 million contract he signed was the richest in baseball history at the time.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] He played at a high level in his three years with Texas, winning his first AL MVP Award win in 2003, but the team failed to make the playoffs.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] Before the 2004 season, Rodriguez was traded to the Yankees, for whom he converted to a third baseman to accommodate their shortstop Derek Jeter.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] He opted out of his contract after the 2007 season, then signed a new 10-year, $275 million deal with the Yankees, breaking his own record for the sport's most lucrative contract.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] He became the youngest player to hit 500 home runs, reaching the milestone in 2007.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] He helped the Yankees win the 2009 World Series over the Philadelphia Phillies, Rodriguez's only championship title.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] Toward the end of his career, he was hampered by hip and knee injuries, which caused him to become exclusively a designated hitter.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] He played his final game in professional baseball on August 12, 2016.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] Despite denying in a 2007 interview that he had ever used performance-enhancing drugs, Rodriguez admitted in 2009 to having used steroids, saying he used them from 2001 to 2003 when playing for the Rangers due to "an enormous amount of pressure" to perform.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] While recovering from a hip injury in 2013, Rodriguez made headlines by feuding with team management over his rehabilitation and for having allegedly obtained performance-enhancing drugs as part of the Biogenesis scandal.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] In August 2013, MLB announced a 211-game suspension for Rodriguez for his involvement in the scandal.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] After an arbitration hearing, the suspension was reduced to 162 games, which kept him off the field for the entire 2014 season.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] After retiring as a player, Rodriguez became a media personality, serving as a broadcaster for Fox Sports, a cast member of *Shark Tank* and a contributor to ABC News.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] In January 2018, ESPN announced that Rodriguez would be joining the broadcast team of *Sunday Night Baseball*.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] Rodriguez was born on July 27, 1975, in the Washington Heights section of Manhattan to Dominican immigrants Víctor Manuel Rodríguez Marcano and Lourdes Nelly Navarro Melo from San Juan de la Maguana, Dominican Republic.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] He was raised alongside his two half-siblings, Joe and Suzy, from his mother's first marriage.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] In 1979, when he was four years old, the family moved to the Dominican Republic, then to Miami, Florida, when he was in the fourth grade.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] His father played baseball for a team in the Dominican Republic and introduced him to the sport as a child.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] Growing up, Rodriguez's favorite baseball players were Keith Hernandez, Dale Murphy, and Cal Ripken Jr., and his favorite team was the New York Mets.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] At the end of his freshman year at Christopher Columbus High School in Miami, Rodriguez transferred to Westminster Christian School in Palmetto Bay, Florida, where he was a star shortstop on the baseball team and played quarterback on the football team.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] In 100 games he batted .419 with 90 stolen bases.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] Westminster won the high school national championship in his junior year.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] He was first team prep All-American as a senior, hitting .505 with nine home runs, 36 runs batted in (RBIs), and 35 stolen bases in 35 attempts in 33 games.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] He was selected as the USA Baseball Junior Player of the Year and as Gatorade's national baseball student-athlete of the year.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] In 1993, Rodriguez became the first high school player to try out for the United States national baseball team.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] He was regarded as the top prospect in the country.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] Rodriguez signed a letter of intent to play baseball for University of Miami and was also recruited by Miami to play quarterback for its football team.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p01] Rodriguez turned down the University of Miami baseball scholarship offer and never played college baseball, opting instead to sign with the Seattle Mariners after being selected first overall in the 1993 amateur draft at the age of 17.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The Seattle Mariners selected Rodriguez with the first overall selection of the 1993 Major League Baseball draft.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The Mariners signed him to a three-year contract worth $1.3 million, and a $1 million signing bonus.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In 1994, Rodriguez made his professional baseball debut as a minor league player with the Appleton Foxes of the Class A Midwest League.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He was promoted to the Jacksonville Suns of the Double-A Southern League.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He played in 17 games for Jacksonville, then was promoted to the Triple-A Calgary Cannons for 32 games before moving up to the major leagues.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On July 8, Rodriguez debuted in the major leagues as a starting shortstop, just the third 18-year-old major league shortstop since 1900.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He was also the first 18-year-old major league player since 1978 and the youngest position player in Seattle history.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He remains the last 18-year-old to play in an MLB game, as of the end of the 2025 season.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez recorded his first major league hit when he singled off of Sergio Valdez on July 9 at Fenway Park.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez played in 17 games for the Mariners, compiling a .204 batting average, two RBIs, and three stolen bases.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In August, The Mariners optioned Rodriguez to Triple-A Calgary.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In 32 games for Calgary, he had 37 hits in 119 at-bats for a .311 batting average.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He also compiled six home runs and 21 RBIs.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez split most of the 1995 season between the Mariners and the Tacoma Rainiers of the PCL.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He hit his first major league home run off Kansas City's Tom Gordon on June 12.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez permanently joined the Mariners roster in August and got his first taste of postseason play, albeit just two at-bats.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Again, he was the youngest player in MLB.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] During the 1995 season, Rodriguez played 48 games for Seattle, batting .232 with five home runs, 19 RBI, and four stolen bases.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The following year, Rodriguez took over as the Mariners' regular shortstop and had his breakout season.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He led the American League (AL) with a .358 batting average, the highest for an AL right-handed batter since Joe DiMaggio hit .381 in 1939 and the tenth-highest ever for a shortstop.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] At 21 years and one month, he was the third youngest AL batting leader ever behind Al Kaline (20) in 1955 and Ty Cobb (20) in 1907, and the third-youngest player in history with 35+ homers.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He was also the first major league shortstop to win a batting title since 1960, and the first in the AL since 1944.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] At age 20 years, 11 months, he was the youngest shortstop in All-Star Game history.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He also led the AL in runs (141), total bases (379), and doubles (54) and ranked among the league leaders in base hits (second, 215), extra-base hits (second, 91), multi-hit games (third, 65), slugging (fourth, .631), RBI (eighth, 123), and on-base percentage (eighth, .414).
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The *Sporting News* and Associated Press selected Rodriguez as their Major League Player of the Year.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He finished second to Juan González in balloting for the AL Most Valuable Player (MVP) Award.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He finished three points behind González (290–287), matching the second-closest AL MVP voting in history.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In 1997, Rodriguez batted .300 with 23 home runs and 84 RBIs.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He hit for the cycle on June 5, becoming the second Mariner, and at 21 years, 10 months, the fifth-youngest player in history, to accomplish the feat.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He was voted by fans to start the All-Star Game at shortstop for the AL team, becoming the first player other than Ripken to start at shortstop in 13 years.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] It was the first All-Star start of his career and his second consecutive All-Star Game.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez rebounded in 1998, when he set the AL record for homers by a shortstop and became just the third member of the 40–40 club, (with 42 home runs and 46 stolen bases) and one of three shortstops in history to hit 40 home runs in a season.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] His 43.9 Power-speed number was, until 2023, the highest single-season power–speed number.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He was selected as Players Choice AL Player of the Year, won his second Silver Slugger Award, and finished ninth in the MVP voting.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In 1999, Rodriguez had a .310 average, 42 home runs, and 111 RBIs, despite missing over 30 games with an injury and playing the second half of the season at Safeco Field, a considerably less hitter-friendly ballpark than the Kingdome.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] At the time, he was the youngest-ever player to record 100 home runs and 100 stolen bases, at 23 years and 309 days of age.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] That record lasted until April 2015, when Mike Trout reached the same milestone at 23 years and 253 days old.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez entered 2000 as the cornerstone of the Mariners franchise, which had recently traded future Hall of Famers Randy Johnson and Ken Griffey Jr.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez produced great numbers, hitting 41 home runs with 132 RBIs and a .316 batting average.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He set a career high for walks (100) and became the only shortstop to have 100 runs, RBI, and walks in the same season.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He hit well in the playoffs as well (.409 batting average and .773 slugging percentage), but Seattle lost to the New York Yankees in the AL Championship Series (ALCS).
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He was selected as the Major League Player of the Year by *Baseball America* and finished third in the AL MVP voting.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez became a free agent after the 2000 season.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He eventually signed with the Texas Rangers, who had just finished in last place in the AL West.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The contract was at the time the most lucrative contract in sports history: a 10-year deal worth $252 million (equivalent to $471 million in 2025).
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The deal was worth $63 million more than the second-richest baseball deal.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The contract was highly criticized, because it tied up valuable payroll space that could have been spent to improve other areas, such as pitching.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Dave McNally, one of the players who had successfully challenged the reserve clause in the 1970s to create free agency in baseball, said, "My first thought when I saw [reports that Rodriguez had signed] was: Did Texas offer him $250 million and he wanted two more?
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In an interview eight years later, Rodriguez said he regretted signing with Texas and wished he had signed with the New York Mets instead, and that he had heeded the advice of his agent, Scott Boras.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez's power-hitting numbers improved with his move to the Texas Rangers.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In his first season there, Rodriguez produced one of the top offensive seasons ever for a shortstop, leading the AL with 52 home runs, 133 runs scored, and 393 total bases.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] His 52 homers made him the sixth youngest to ever reach 50 homers and were the highest total ever by a shortstop, surpassing Ernie Banks' record of 47 in 1958, and also the most ever for an infielder other than a first baseman, breaking Phillies 3B Mike Schmidt's mark of 48 in 1980.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] It was his fifth 30-homer campaign, tying Banks for most ever by a shortstop.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He also tied for the league lead in extra-base hits (87) and ranked third in RBIs (135) and slugging (.622).
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He was also among the AL leaders in hits (fourth, 201), average (seventh, .318), and on-base percentage (eighth, .399).
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He established Rangers club records for homers, runs, total bases, and hit by pitches, had the second-most extra-base hits, and the fourth-highest RBI total.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He led the club in runs, hits, doubles (34), homers, RBI, slugging, and on-base percentage and was second in walks (75), stolen bases (18), and game-winning RBI (14) while posting career highs for homers, RBI, and total bases.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez started 161 games at shortstop and one as the DH, the only major league player to start all of his team's games in 2001.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez followed the previous year with a major league-best 57 home runs, 142 RBIs and 389 total bases in 2002, becoming the first player to lead the majors in all three categories since 1984.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] His nine home runs in April matched a team record that was shared (through 2008) with Iván Rodríguez (2000), Carl Everett (2003), and Ian Kinsler (2007).
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He had the sixth-most home runs in AL history, the most since Roger Maris' then-league record 61 in 1961 and the most ever for a shortstop for the second straight year.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He won the Babe Ruth Home Run Award for leading MLB in homers that season.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He also won his first Gold Glove Award, awarded for outstanding defense.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] His 109 home runs in 2001–02 were the most ever by an AL right-handed batter in consecutive seasons (later surpassed by Aaron Judge in 2024–2025).
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] However, the Rangers finished last in the AL West division in both years.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He finished second in the MVP balloting to fellow shortstop Miguel Tejada, whose 103-win Oakland Athletics won the same division.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The 2003 season was Rodriguez's last year with the Rangers.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He led the AL in home runs, runs scored, and slugging percentage, and won his second consecutive Gold Glove Award.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He also led the league in fewest at-bats per home run (12.9) and became the youngest player to hit 300 homers.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He was tied with Jim Thome for the MLB lead in homers, and he won his second Babe Ruth Home Run Award.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Following five top-10 finishes in the AL MVP voting between 1996 and 2002, Rodriguez won his first MVP trophy.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez, a two-time runner up in the balloting by the Baseball Writers' Association of America, joined outfielder Andre Dawson from the 1987 Chicago Cubs as the only players to play on last-place teams and win the award.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Following the 2003 season, Texas set out to part ways with Rodriguez and his expensive contract.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The Rangers initially agreed to a trade with the Boston Red Sox, sending Rodriguez to Boston for Manny Ramirez, 19-year old pitching prospect Jon Lester, and cash considerations.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] However, the MLB Players Association vetoed the deal because it called for a voluntary reduction in salary by Rodriguez.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Despite the failed deal with the Red Sox, the Rangers named him team captain during that off-season.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Yankees third baseman Aaron Boone suffered a knee injury while playing a game of pickup basketball that sidelined him for the entire 2004 season, creating a hole at third base.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On February 15, 2004, the Rangers traded Rodriguez to the New York Yankees for second baseman Alfonso Soriano and a player to be named later (Joaquín Árias was sent to the Rangers on March 24).
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The Rangers also agreed to pay $67 million of the $179 million left on Rodriguez's contract.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez agreed to switch positions from shortstop to third base, paving the way for the trade, because the popular Derek Jeter was already entrenched at shortstop.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] This was only the second time in MLB history that a reigning MVP was traded, with the first coming in 1914 when Eddie Collins was traded to the Chicago White Sox from the Philadelphia Athletics for cash considerations.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez also had to switch uniform numbers; he had worn 3 his entire career, but the number was retired by the Yankees in honor of Babe Ruth.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Instead, Rodriguez chose to change his number to 13, in honor of Miami Dolphins quarterback Dan Marino.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] As a Miami native, Rodriguez had grown up watching Marino and also wore number 13 when he played quarterback in high school.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] During his first season with the Yankees, Rodriguez hit .286 with 36 home runs, 106 RBIs, 112 runs scored and 28 stolen bases.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He became one of only three players in major league history to compile at least 35 home runs, 100 runs and 100 RBIs in seven consecutive seasons, joining Hall of Famers Babe Ruth and Jimmie Foxx.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The 112 runs marked the ninth straight season in which he scored at least 100 runs, the longest such streak in MLB since Hank Aaron did it in 13 straight seasons from 1955 to 1967, and the longest in the AL since Mickey Mantle did it also in nine straight seasons from 1953 to 1961.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] During the 2004 season, he also became the youngest player ever to reach 350 home runs and the third youngest to reach 1,000 RBIs.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He was elected to the AL All-Star Team, the eighth All-Star selection of his career and the first as a third baseman.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On July 24, 2004, Rodriguez was hit by a pitch from Bronson Arroyo, which led to a scuffle with Boston Red Sox catcher Jason Varitek, and a bench-clearing brawl between both teams.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On defense, he had the lowest range factor among non-platoon AL third basemen (2.39) in his first year at the position.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He finished 14th in balloting for the AL MVP Award.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In the AL Division Series (ALDS), Rodriguez was a dominant hitter against the Minnesota Twins, batting .421 and slugging .737 while delivering two key extra-inning hits.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez's first season with the Yankees culminated in a dramatic playoff series against the team he had almost ended up playing for: the Yankees' bitter rival, the Boston Red Sox.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In that ALCS, he equaled the single-game post-season record with five runs scored in Game 3 at Boston.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] One of the most controversial plays of Rodriguez's career occurred late in Game 6 of the ALCS.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] With one out and Derek Jeter on first base in the bottom of the eighth inning, Rodriguez hit a slow roller between the pitcher's mound and the first-base line.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Red Sox pitcher Bronson Arroyo fielded the ball and ran towards Rodriguez to apply a tag.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] As Arroyo reached towards him, Rodriguez swatted at his glove, knocking the ball loose.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] As the ball rolled away, Jeter scored all the way from first as Rodriguez took second on the play, which was initially ruled an error on Arroyo.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] However, the umpires quickly huddled, then ruled that Rodriguez was out for interference.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Jeter was sent back to first base, and his run was nullified.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The Yankees would then lose the ALCS to the eventual World Series champion Red Sox after leading the series three games to none.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In 2005, Rodriguez hit .321, leading the AL with 124 runs and 48 home runs while driving in 130 runs.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He became the first Yankee to win the AL home run title since Reggie Jackson (41) in 1980.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He also became one of only two players in major league history to compile at least 35 home runs, 100 runs and 100 RBIs in eight consecutive seasons (Jimmie Foxx accomplished the feat in nine straight seasons from 1932 to 1940).
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez set the franchise record for most home runs in a single season by a right-handed batter, surpassing Joe DiMaggio's mark of 46 in 1937.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] (Judge hit 62 in 2022.) His 47 home runs from the third base position are a single-season AL record.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez hit 26 home runs at Yankee Stadium, establishing the single-season club record for right-handed batters (previously held by DiMaggio in 1937 and Gary Sheffield in 2004 and surpassed by Judge at the new Yankee Stadium in 2022).
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On June 8, at 29 years, 316 days old, he became the youngest player in MLB history to reach the 400 home run mark.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] 2005 also marked the tenth straight season that Rodriguez scored at least 100 runs.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On defense, however, he had the lowest range factor in the league at third for the second straight season (2.62).
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On April 26, Rodriguez hit three home runs off Angels pitcher Bartolo Colón and drove in 10 runs.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The 10 RBIs were the most by a Yankee since Tony Lazzeri established the franchise and AL record with 11 on May 24, 1936.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez became the 11th major leaguer to accomplish the feat.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez won his second AL MVP Award in three seasons, becoming the fifth player to win this award with two different teams, joining Mickey Cochrane, Jimmie Foxx, Frank Robinson and Barry Bonds.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He also became the first AL player from outside the AL West to win the award since Mo Vaughn of the Boston Red Sox won in 1995.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez was also named the shortstop on the MLB Latino Legends Team in 2005.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Prior to the season, Rodriguez played for the U.S. in the 2006 World Baseball Classic.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez was again an All-Star in 2006.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] His 2,000th hit, on July 21, 2006 − six days prior to his 31st birthday − was also his 450th home run.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez became the youngest player in baseball history to reach 450 home runs (surpassing Ken Griffey Jr., by 267 days), and the eighth player to reach 2,000 hits before turning 31.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Ty Cobb reached the mark while still 29, while Rogers Hornsby, Mel Ott, Hank Aaron, Joe Medwick, Jimmie Foxx, and Robin Yount all achieved their 2,000th hit at age 30.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] All seven are members of baseball's Hall of Fame.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] For the season, Rodriguez finished fourth in the league in RBI (121), fifth in runs scored (113), eighth in home runs (35) and walks (90), and ninth in OBP (.392).
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He also led all AL third basemen in errors, with 24, and had the lowest fielding percentage (.937) and—for the third straight season—range factor (2.50) among them.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez also became the second player in major league history to record at least 35 home runs, 100 runs, and 100 RBIs in nine consecutive seasons, joining Foxx.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] It was Rodriguez's 11th consecutive season with more than 100 runs scored, the longest such streak in AL history since Lou Gehrig did so in 13 straight seasons (1926–38).
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Despite this success, it was perceived as one of his lesser-accomplished seasons and was harshly criticized throughout the 2006 season.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He has commented that 2006 was his most difficult season as a professional.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] When Rodriguez reported to camp in 2007, he had reduced his body fat from 16% the year before to 9%.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He made light of this fact during a *Late Show with David Letterman* sketch that was filmed during Spring training, which featured him shirtless being rubbed down with suntan lotion.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He revealed to the press that he and Jeter were no longer close friends.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez also reduced his high leg kick at the plate, increasing his bat speed, making him less-apt to strike out and a more dangerous hitter.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In the Yankees' fourth game of the season, Rodriguez hit two home runs against the Baltimore Orioles at Yankee Stadium, including his 14th-career grand slam to end the game.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The walk-off grand slam was the third of his career, tying the major league mark for game-ending grand slams shared by Vern Stephens and Cy Williams.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez also began the season by becoming the ninth major leaguer—and first Yankee—to hit six home runs in the first seven games of the season.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez also became the first Yankee to hit seven home runs in the first ten games of the season.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On April 23, Rodriguez became the first player in major league history to hit 14 home runs in a span of 18 games, and also tied the MLB record for most home runs in April.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] His total of 34 RBIs in April was one short of Juan González's MLB record.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In a game against the Toronto Blue Jays on May 30, Rodriguez sparked controversy when he shouted during a routine play and an infielder let a pop fly drop, costing the Blue Jays three runs.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The Yankees went on to win the game, 10–5.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On July 12, Rodriguez hit his 150th career home run in a Yankees uniform.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] This made him the first, and so far only, player in major league history to ever hit 150 home runs for three different teams.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He became the third player to hit at least 100 home runs for three teams, following Reggie Jackson and Darrell Evans.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez hit his 500th career home run against pitcher Kyle Davies of the Kansas City Royals on August 4.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez became the youngest player ever to reach 500 home runs at 32 years, 8 days.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He surpassed the nearly 67-year record held by Jimmie Foxx, who hit his 500th home run at 32 years, 338 days during the final week of the 1940 MLB season.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On September 25, Rodriguez became the fifth MLB player to record a 50-home run, 150-RBI season when he hit a grand slam.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez is the most recent player to have recorded at least 150 RBIs in one season, as of 2025.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In 2007, Rodriguez became the first player in major league history to have at least 35 home runs, 100 runs, and 100 RBIs in 10 consecutive seasons, surpassing Jimmie Foxx (nine consecutive seasons).
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He led MLB in home runs and won his third Babe Ruth Home Run Award.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] After the season, Rodriguez was named the AL MVP for the third time in his career, receiving 26 first-place votes out of a possible 28.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He also won the Silver Slugger Award for his position, the Players Choice Award for Outstanding AL Player, and the Players Choice Award for Player of the Year.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The 2007 season marked the last year of Rodriguez's 10-year, $252 million contract before he opted out and became a free agent again.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez had repeatedly stated during the 2007 season that he would like to remain a Yankee for the rest of his career.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On October 28, Rodriguez's agent, Scott Boras, announced that he would not renew his contract with the Yankees citing that he "was unsure of the future composition" of the team.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Because of the opt-out, the Yankees also lost $21.3 million in remaining payments from the Rangers as part of their agreement from the 2004 trade.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez received a slew of criticism from fans and writers alike not only for opting out, but also for not meeting with Yankee management before he did.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Teammate Mariano Rivera convinced Rodriguez to contact the New York Yankees ownership.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He contacted them directly, bypassing Boras (Boras also apologized for the timing of the announcement).
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Subsequently, Rodriguez issued a statement on his website, saying that he wished to stay with the Yankees.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On November 15, the Yankees and Rodriguez agreed on the "basic framework" of a 10-year, $275 million contract (equivalent to $514 million in 2025) that would have him playing until he was 42.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The contract, finalized December 13, included various multimillion-dollar incentives for breaking career home run milestones.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez hit his 549th home run in a September 3, 2008, game against the Tampa Bay Rays.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The opposing manager objected that the ball was foul, and for the first time in MLB history, instant replay (a process officially introduced a few days earlier) was used to review the play and uphold the umpires' ruling.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He was one of only four batters in the AL to have at least 18 home runs and 18 stolen bases in both 2007 and 2008, along with Torii Hunter, Ian Kinsler, and Grady Sizemore.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez hit a home run every 14.6 at-bats in 2008, the second-best ratio on the team behind Jason Giambi.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez played 138 games during the 2008 season with a .302 average, 35 home runs, 103 RBI, and an AL best .573 slugging percentage.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On February 7, 2009, *Sports Illustrated* reported that Rodriguez tested positive for testosterone and the anabolic steroid Primobolan in 2003.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez's name appears on a government-sealed list of 104 major-league players (out of 1200 tested) who came up positive for performance-enhancing drugs.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The report was compiled as part of MLB's 2003 survey to determine whether a mandatory random drug testing program might be necessary.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] At the time, there was no penalty or punishment for a positive steroid test.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez did not immediately confirm the allegations, deferring at first to the players' union.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Two days after the allegations, Rodriguez admitted to steroid use from 2001 to 2003, claiming that he ceased using such substances after spring training that year.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Prior to the 2009 season, Rodriguez was scheduled to represent the Dominican Republic in the 2009 World Baseball Classic, but he was forced to withdraw when an MRI revealed a cyst in his right hip.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] When he went to have the cyst drained, it was discovered that he was also suffering from a torn labrum in the same hip.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez opted to undergo an arthroscopic procedure with a recovery period of six to nine weeks, instead of the usual three to four months.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Although the procedure should have allowed him to make it through the season without any complications, he required a second, more extensive surgery in the off-season.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] After missing spring training and the first month of the season, Rodriguez returned to the Yankees in a May 8 game against the Baltimore Orioles and hit a three-run home run on the first pitch of his first at-bat.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The Yankees had stumbled to a 13–15 record in Rodriguez's absence, and his return fortified the lineup and provided much-needed protection for three-hole hitter Mark Teixeira, who was a notoriously slow starter.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez also supplied some late-game heroics.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On May 16, his two-run walk-off home run in the bottom of the eleventh inning gave the Yankees a 6–4 win over the Minnesota Twins.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] One week later, he hit a game-tying solo home run in the bottom of the ninth off Philadelphia Phillies closer Brad Lidge in a game the Yankees would go on to win, 5–4.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] By early June, the Yankees had surged to first place in the AL East.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The club's fortunes changed later in the month, when Rodriguez fell into a slump that saw his batting average plummet as the Yankees fell to second place.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On June 23, Rodriguez became the eighth active player to reach 8,000 career at-bats in the seventh inning of the Yankees and Braves game.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On June 25, Rodriguez belted homer 563 of his career, off Atlanta Braves starter Derek Lowe, and tying Reggie Jackson for 11th on the all-time home run list.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Dating back to Game 4 of the 2004 ALCS, Rodriguez had batted with 38 runners on base over a span of 61 postseason at-bats.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He stranded every one of them, going 0-for-29 with runners on base.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] However, in the first game of the 2009 ALDS against Minnesota, he hit two RBI singles, both with two outs.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In Game 2, he hit an RBI single in the sixth, and hit a game-tying homer off closer Joe Nathan in the bottom of the ninth inning.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In Game 3, he again hit a game-tying home run.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In the ALCS, Rodriguez hit his third game-tying home run of the postseason in Game 2 in the bottom of the 11th against Angels closer Brian Fuentes.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] For the series, he batted 9–21 (.429) with three home runs and six runs batted in.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The Yankees faced the Phillies in the World Series.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In Game 3, Rodriguez hit what appeared to be a double off a camera perched atop the outfield wall, but after protest by Yankee manager Joe Girardi, the play was reviewed and ruled a home run.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In Game 4, Rodriguez drove in the go-ahead run with two outs in the ninth inning off closer Brad Lidge.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The Yankees would go on to win the game 7–4 to take a 3-games-to-1 lead in the series.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Despite a 2–4 performance with three RBI in Game 5, the Yankees lost 8–6 to force the Series to return to the Bronx for Game 6.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez was 1–2 with 2 walks and two runs scored in Game 6, as the Yankees went on to defeat the Phillies 7–3 for their 27th World Series championship, the only one of Rodriguez's career.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Having reversed his postseason misfortunes, he was the Babe Ruth Award winner as the 2009 postseason MVP, in which he batted .365 with six home runs and 18 RBI.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On August 4, 2010, on the three-year anniversary of his 500th home run, Rodriguez became the seventh player in major league history to hit 600 home runs, hitting number 600 off Shaun Marcum of the Toronto Blue Jays, becoming the youngest player to do so at 35 years and 8 days old.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On August 14, Rodriguez hit three home runs in a game against the Kansas City Royals.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In the top of the sixth, he hit his first, a solo dinger to left center.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In the top of the seventh, he hit his second, a two-run shot to dead center.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In the top of the ninth, he hit his third, a towering two-run blast into the waterfall in Kauffman Stadium.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On September 6, he recorded his 100th RBI; it was the 14th year he had reached the mark, the most times of any player in baseball history.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On September 29, he hit his 30th home run of the season, recording his MLB-record 13th straight year of at least 30 home runs and 100 RBIs, breaking a tie with Jimmie Foxx, who had 12 seasons.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In 2011, Rodriguez batted .295 with 13 home runs and 52 RBIs prior to the All-Star break.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Despite good production, Rodriguez suffered the longest single-season home run drought of his career by not hitting one in 85 at-bats.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Although elected to start the game, Rodriguez opted for arthroscopic surgery on his knee to repair a torn meniscus that impacted his power, and was placed on the disabled list.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On top of recovery, Rodriguez was facing serious allegations that he participated in illegal, underground poker games.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] One of those games reportedly turned violent and cocaine was openly used.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] However, Rodriguez denied through a representative that he ever participated in illegal poker games.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] An MLB Executive has said that if Rodriguez was indeed proven guilty, he may face a suspension; MLB had warned Rodriguez in 2005 not to participate in such games.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez returned to the Yankees on August 21, playing third base against the Minnesota Twins, going 0-for-4.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He sustained another injury with a jammed thumb while trying to make a play in that game.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He returned to the Yankees on August 25, going 2-for-4 with two singles in a win for the Yankees over the Oakland Athletics.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On August 26, Rodriguez hit his first home run since coming off the disabled list, a solo shot off Baltimore Orioles pitcher Tommy Hunter.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He concluded the season with 16 home runs and 62 RBIs in 99 games, ending his MLB-record streak of 13 straight seasons of 30 homers and 100 RBIs.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez hit his 23rd career grand slam off Atlanta Braves relief pitcher Jonny Venters on June 12, 2012, which tied Lou Gehrig for the most in MLB history.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In a road loss versus the Seattle Mariners on July 24, 2012, Rodriguez took a hit to the hand during an eighth-inning at bat versus Seattle starting pitcher Félix Hernández.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The injury was later described as a non-displaced fracture.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez was placed on the disabled list.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Earlier in the same game, Hernandez struck out Rodriguez in the sixth inning, making Rodriguez the fifth player to record 2,000 career strikeouts in MLB history.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] During the 2012 postseason, Rodriguez was removed for a pinch hitter multiple times and did not start many times.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He batted 3-for-25 overall, and went 0-for-18 with 12 strikeouts against right-handed pitchers.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The Yankees were eliminated by the Tigers in the 2012 ALCS.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On January 16, 2013, Rodriguez underwent arthroscopic surgery in his hip to repair a torn labrum.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] It was the second time in four years that he had the surgery, although the operation was more serious than before.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez began the 2013 season on the 60-day disabled list.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] While rehabilitating his hip, Rodriguez was embroiled in a series of negative headlines: he became a central figure of the Biogenesis scandal and MLB's investigation into his possible connection to performance-enhancing drugs.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Around the same time, Rodriguez announced on Twitter that his doctor had medically cleared him to play in games.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Yankees general manager Brian Cashman, much to his dismay, soon revealed that Rodriguez's doctor did not have such authority to clear him.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez played his first rehab assignment game on July 2, 2013, with the Yankees Class-A Low affiliate, the Charleston RiverDogs.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He continued his rehabilitation and played for the Yankees Triple-A team, the Scranton/Wilkes-Barre RailRiders on July 18.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Two days prior to his scheduled promotion to the major league roster, Rodriguez sustained a new injury, as an MRI later revealed a Grade 1 quad strain, delaying his return and forcing him to continue rehabilitating in the minor leagues.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez independently sought a second opinion on his quad strain on July 24 with a doctor who stated that there did not appear to be an injury; the Yankees front office expressed further dismay, claiming that he violated league rules for seeking a second opinion without the team's permission.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He completed his rehabilitation program with the Yankees' Double-A affiliate Trenton Thunder.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez made his 2013 return with the Yankees on August 5, which was the same day that MLB announced he would be suspended—pending an appeal—through the 2014 season for his role in the Biogenesis scandal.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On August 11, Rodriguez hit his first home run of the season off Detroit Tigers pitcher Justin Verlander.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] With the home run, Rodriguez passed Stan Musial for fifth place in career RBIs.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez continued to feud with the Yankees front office following his return, as his lawyers accused the team, and specifically Christopher S.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Ahmad, of mishandling his hip injury in several ways; Rodriguez's legal team contended that the team withheld the injury from him and continued to play him in 2012, despite his condition.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Yankees team president Randy Levine expressed negative comments towards Rodriguez, saying that he would "feel happy if Rodriguez never played again".
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In response to the accusations, Cashman said, "I'm not comfortable talking to Alex about this because we feel we are in a litigious environment.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Hello and goodbye, that's about it." He added, "It's not just Yankees' management.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He's putting it at the level of our trainers, our medical staff.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] During a game against the Red Sox on August 18, Rodriguez was involved in key moments against Ryan Dempster.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The first time he faced Dempster, Rodriguez was hit by a pitch on a 3–0 count, leading to home plate umpire Brian O'Nora warning both benches and ejecting Girardi, while Dempster was allowed to stay in the game.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Later in the top of the sixth inning, Rodriguez encountered Dempster again, hitting a 442-foot home run to straightaway center.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The Yankees won 9–6, and Dempster, who hit Rodriguez before, was suspended five games by the league with an undisclosed fine (although he did not miss a start).
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On September 20, at Yankee Stadium, Rodriguez hit his 24th career grand slam, an opposite field 654th career home run, off George Kontos of the San Francisco Giants, breaking the all-time grand slam record, formerly held by Lou Gehrig.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] For the 2013 season, Rodriguez played in only 44 games batting .244 with seven home runs and 19 RBI.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez's suspension that was announced the previous season but delayed pending an appeal, was upheld, resulting in him being suspended for the entirety of the 2014 regular season and postseason.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] At the end of the 2014 season, general manager Brian Cashman announced that Rodriguez would no longer serve as an everyday third baseman after the team's signing of Chase Headley, and would instead serve as a designated hitter.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In the off-season, during the week of January 19, 2015, it was reported that Rodriguez met with new Commissioner of Baseball Rob Manfred.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The pair reportedly had a "positive discussion...in which Rodriguez apologized, while promising to behave in the future".
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On February 17, 2015, Rodriguez issued a hand-written letter of apology to "Major League Baseball, the Yankees, the Steinbrenner family, the Players Association and you, the fans".
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez reported to New York Yankees' 2015 spring training camp three days early.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Girardi planned to play Rodriguez at first base during spring training to assess whether he could be played there, a first for his career.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez played his first game after his suspension on opening day against the Blue Jays at Yankee Stadium.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He served as the designated hitter, going 1 for 2 with a walk as the Yankees lost to the Blue Jays 1–6.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On April 17, his first multi-HR game – and third and fourth home runs – of the season included a blast off Nate Karns of Tampa Bay that traveled 471 feet (144 m), providing four total RBIs in a 5–4 win.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In a pinch-hit appearance against the Red Sox on May 1, Rodriguez hit his 660th career home run off reliever Junichi Tazawa, tying Willie Mays for fourth place on the all-time home run list.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On May 7, Rodriguez hit his 661st career home run off Orioles pitcher Chris Tillman for sole possession of fourth place on the all-time home run list.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On May 27, Rodriguez set an AL record for the most career RBI, passing Lou Gehrig, also moving him into third on the all-time list.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] With his 666th career home run against Bud Norris of the Orioles on June 13, Rodriguez drove in his 2,000th and 2,001st career runs.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] However, opinions varied on whether he was the second (Elias Sports Bureau, trailing Aaron), third (MLB, trailing Aaron and Ruth), or fourth player (Baseball-Reference.com, trailing Aaron, Ruth, and Cap Anson) in MLB history to attain 2,000 RBIs.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez's next home run was also his 3,000th career hit, making him the 29th player to reach the milestone.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He hit it against the Tigers' Justin Verlander in a 7–2 win, joining Wade Boggs and Jeter – both former Yankees – as the only players to hit a home run for his 3,000th hit.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] With his next hit on June 20, Rodriguez surpassed Roberto Clemente, the eleventh player in MLB history to have recorded 3,000 hits.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On July 25, against the Twins in Minnesota, and two days before his 40th birthday, Rodríguez became the fifth-oldest player to hit three home runs in one game.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In his first 95 games of the season, Rodriguez hit 24 homers and produced an OPS of .930.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] After being mired in a 72-at-bat slump without a home run until August 18 against the Twins, he hit his 25th home run which was also his 25th career grand slam, extending his MLB record.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The home run also drove in the go-ahead runs for an 8–4 Yankees win.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] From August 1 until the end of the season, Rodriguez appeared in 56 games, batting .191, .678 OPS, nine home runs, and struck out 59 times in 183 at-bats.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The first base experiment yielded two total appearances in 2015.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He finished with 33 home runs, 86 RBI, 131 hits, and a .252 batting average.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] He led the Yankees in home runs, on-base percentage, slugging percentage, on-base plus slugging, and bases-on-balls.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez reached 30+ home runs for the 15th time in his career, tying Aaron for the most 30-home-run seasons in history.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On April 17, 2016, Rodriguez became the 19th player to make 12,000 career plate appearances.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On May 4, the Yankees placed him on the 15-day disabled list due to a right hamstring strain.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] On May 24, the Yankees sent him on a rehab assignment to the Double-A Trenton Thunder, and activated him on May 26.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The next day, he hit his 30th career home run at Tropicana Field, which traveled an estimated 440 feet (130 m), as the Yankees defeated Tampa Bay, 4–1.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] However, for much of the season, Rodriguez notably struggled to adequately produce, enduring prolonged slumps as his role dwindled from everyday designated hitter to pinch hitter.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In July, he had two extra base hits, including his 696th career home run.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] At a press conference held on August 7, Rodriguez announced that he would play in his final game for the Yankees on the following Friday, August 12, against the Rays at Yankee Stadium.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] It was also noted that the Yankees would sign him to a new contract that would keep him in the organization through 2017 as a special instructor and advisor.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In the offseason, Rodriguez would join the Yankees' front office as a special advisor.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The club commemorated Rodriguez's final game as a Yankee, thanking him in front of a sold-out crowd for his efforts with a tribute of highlights on the stadium videoboard, a presentation of a framed number 13 jersey, and a base autographed by teammates.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] At the plate, he batted third and started as the designated hitter, going 1-for-4 with an RBI double.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In the ninth inning, he was brought onto the field at third base for one batter − his only defensive appearance for the Yankees in 2016 − and departed the field to a "raucous ovation" from the fans.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The next day, the Yankees granted him his unconditional release.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] His vacated roster spot was filled by future MVP Aaron Judge.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Like he said Friday night, he is happy and he is going to take some time to relax and hang with his family and friends." Rodriguez ended the season playing 65 games with a .200 batting average, nine home runs and 31 RBIs.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In January 2017, Rodriguez's spokesman said that he would not play for any other team in the coming year, and would remain a "special advisor" to Yankees owner Hal Steinbrenner.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez became a guest judge on *Shark Tank* in 2017.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] That same year, he signed a deal with ABC News network to serve as a contributor to *ABC World News Tonight*, *Good Morning America*, and *Nightline*.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez is an MLB studio analyst for Fox Sports, working alongside Kevin Burkhardt, David Ortiz and Derek Jeter.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] During his tenure as analyst, Fox Sports' MLB studio show won back-to-back Sports Emmy Awards for Outstanding Studio Show during the network's coverage of the 2016 and 2017 postseason.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez was nominated for an Emmy for Outstanding Sports Personality, Studio and Sports Event Analyst in 2019.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez joined ESPN in 2018 as a *Sunday Night Baseball* analyst, alongside Matt Vasgersian and Buster Olney.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In the 2022 season, Rodriguez moved to a simulcast on ESPN2 that he co-hosts with Michael Kay.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In January 2017, CNBC announced Rodriguez would be the host of the show *Back in the Game*.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The first episode debuted on the network in March 2018.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The series focuses on Rodriguez mentoring athletes and entertainers who have fallen on hard times.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] A four-episode series debuted in November 2019 and featured Evander Holyfield, Ryan Lochte, Brian Dunkleman, and Nicole Eggert.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In July 2020, it was announced that Rodriguez would be part of the judging panel for the *Forbes* Next 1000 list, a franchise which focuses on entrepreneurs from marginalized communities.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez appeared in *The Captain*, a 2022 miniseries about Jeter's life and career.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez and Jeter discussed the rift in their friendship.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez is the subject of the 2025 documentary series *Alex vs ARod*.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez was featured in a 2010 Pepsi Cola commercial as a truck driver in a fleet of delivery trucks simulating players in a baseball game.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] At the end of the commercial when he drives his vehicle to make a catch, he is told by his approving partner in the truck that he has a future in the beverage delivery business.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez is featured in a commercial for *Guitar Hero World Tour*, where he plays the guitar along with athletes Tony Hawk on drums, Kobe Bryant on vocals, and Michael Phelps on guitar.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] The commercial is a spoof of the scene from *Risky Business* where Tom Cruise is dancing to "Old Time Rock and Roll".
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In 2019, Rodriguez was featured in a Planters Super Bowl commercial, where he is watching the game and about to snack on some kale chips but Mr.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Peanut drives in to stop him from eating kale and instead snack on some Peanuts.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In 2020, during Super Bowl LIV, Rodriguez was featured in a Presidente beer Super Bowl commercial, as well as a Hard Rock ad which also featured Jennifer Lopez.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In 2021, Rodriguez teamed up with cosmetics company Hims to launch a line of make-up for men, beginning with its first product – a concealer stick.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In 2022, Rodriguez appeared in a DirecTV commercial with Ortiz and former Mariners teammates Griffey Jr. and Johnson.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Prior to 2009, Rodriguez had received the nickname "The Cooler" among some players because of the perceived tendency for teams to turn cold when he joins them and hot when he leaves.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] According to Yankees manager Joe Torre's 2009 book, *The Yankee Years*, Rodriguez earned the nickname "A-Fraud" from teammates and particularly from clubhouse attendants who were said to resent his demands.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] "It was [said] in front of him," Torre later said of the nickname.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] "A lot of that stuff that went on in the clubhouse was more tongue-in-cheek, fun type stuff," he explained.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Much of the criticism regarding Rodriguez focused on his alleged inability to produce hits in clutch situations.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In 2008, Rodriguez hit only .264 with runners in scoring position and two outs.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] In 95 plate appearances, he walked 20 times and was hit by three pitches, and he had only 19 hits.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Of the 41 times Rodriguez struck out with two outs, 20 came with runners in scoring position.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Because of the Yankees' successful history, he was compared unfavorably to other Yankees greats who have performed exceptionally well in the postseason, such as Reggie Jackson.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] However, after his performance in the 2009 postseason, Rodriguez started receiving many positive comparisons to Reggie Jackson, even being selected as "Mr.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p02] Rodriguez answered many of the criticisms of his postseason performance by performing exceptionally well in the 2009 postseason, where he posted a .365 batting average and hit six home-runs in 52 at-bats during the Yankees' 15 post-season games.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] In July 2007, former outfielder and steroid-user Jose Canseco said that he was planning to publish another book about Major League Baseball (MLB) to follow his 2005 bestseller *Juiced*.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Canseco said his new book would have "other stuff" on Rodriguez, and called him a hypocrite.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] At the time, Rodriguez denied accusations of steroid use.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] In a 2007 interview with Katie Couric, Rodriguez flatly denied ever having used performance-enhancing drugs.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] The information had been part of a government-sealed report detailing 104 major league players (out of 1200 players tested) who tested positive for performance enhancers during a 2003 drug survey.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Approved by the players themselves with the promise of anonymity, the survey was conducted by MLB to see whether a mandatory drug testing program might be necessary.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] At the time, as the result of a collectively bargained union agreement, there was no penalty or punishment for a positive test.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Because more than 5% of the samples taken from players in 2003 came back positive, mandatory testing of major league baseball players began in 2004, with penalties for violations.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] The 2003 test results were supposed to remain anonymous and the samples destroyed.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] However, a coded master list of 104 players was seized during the BALCO investigation, turning up in a 2004 federal raid on Comprehensive Drug Testing's facility in Long Beach, California.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] A month later, the physical samples were seized by federal agents raiding Quest Diagnostics in Las Vegas, Nevada.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] The list of the 104 positive-testing players was released to the MLB Players Association (MLBPA) in 2004.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Although testosterone is available by prescription for some uses, Primobolan has no approved prescription use.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Also known as *methenolone* or *metenolone enanthate*, it is the same steroid that Barry Bonds is alleged to have tested positive for in 2000 and 2001.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] A fairly weak steroid on its own, it is generally used in conjunction with other steroids.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] The drug is generally preferred in injected rather than oral form due to its cost.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] In an interview with ESPN after the report came out, citing "an enormous amount of pressure to perform", Rodriguez admitted to using banned substances from 2001 to 2003.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] "All my years in New York have been clean", he added, saying he had not used banned substances since last taking them following a spring training injury in 2003 while playing for the Rangers.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] "Back then, [baseball] was a different culture", Rodriguez said.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] And I wanted to prove to everyone that I was worth being one of the greatest players of all time.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] And for that, I am very sorry and deeply regretful." Rodriguez said he could not be sure of the name(s) of the substance(s) he had used.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Rodriguez said he was never told that he was among the 104 players who tested positive, only that a tip came in August 2004 from Gene Orza of the MLBPA that he "may or may not have" failed his 2003 test.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Orza was accused by three (unnamed) MLB players of tipping Rodriguez to an upcoming drug test in September 2004; both Orza and the MLBPA have denied the allegations.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Rodriguez absolved the players' union of any blame for leaking his positive test results, saying he alone was responsible for his mistakes.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] MLB commissioner Bud Selig briefly considered whether to punish Rodriguez for his admitted steroid use, citing the illegality of the situation, among other things.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] However, at the time of the testing there were no punishments for this sort of activity.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Additionally, his admission to three years of steroid use could be damaging to his image and legacy.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Later in the month, Rodriguez called a press conference in Tampa, Florida, and in the presence of many supportive Yankee teammates, answered reporters' questions about his 2001–2003 steroid use.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Rodriguez said he and a cousin (whom he refused to name) bought an unidentified drug over-the-counter in the Dominican Republic, where it is "known on the streets as boli or bollee." At Rodriguez's instruction, the cousin transported the drug into the United States.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] For six months of the year, Rodriguez injected himself twice monthly with "boli" (a drug name unfamiliar to experts and perhaps a slang term for Primobolan or Dianabol, although the latter steroid is taken orally).
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Rodriguez said he did not know whether he was using the drug properly or whether it was safe.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Although he "certainly felt more energy", Rodriguez said it would be "hard to say" whether it gave him a competitive edge.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Rodriguez said he would become a spokesperson for the Taylor Hooton foundation, which educates young people about the dangers of steroid use.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] He has since spoken at schools about the dangers of steroids.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] On February 28, 2010, *The New York Times* reported that Rodriguez had received treatment from Canadian sports doctor Anthony Galea in March 2009.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] In 2011, Galea reached a plea agreement for bringing unapproved and mislabeled drugs into the United States, including human growth hormone (HGH) and Actovegin.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Galea confirmed to the Associated Press that he had treated Rodriguez but claimed that he had only prescribed anti-inflammatories.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Between 2010 and 2012, Rodriguez reportedly received HGH from Biogenesis of America, an anti-aging clinic in Coral Gables, Florida, run by Bosch.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] For much of the summer of 2013, it had been expected that Rodriguez would be suspended for his role in the scandal.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] The first definitive confirmation came on August 3, 2013, when MLB rebuffed the players' union's last-minute offer to negotiate.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Instead, it allowed Rodriguez until the afternoon of August 4 to reach an agreement regarding a suspension or greater punishment for his role in the Biogenesis affair.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] On August 5, MLB suspended Rodriguez from August 8 through the end of the 2014 season for violating the league's PED policy, a term that was to include a total of 211 regular-season games plus any postseason games.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] He was one of 13 players suspended for their roles in the scandal.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Almost immediately after the suspension was announced, Rodriguez announced that he would appeal.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] He was the only player to do so; the others accepted season-ending 50-game suspensions without appeal.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Although MLB commissioner Bud Selig had the option of using his best-interests-of-baseball powers to remove Rodriguez from the field immediately, he chose to suspend Rodriguez under the drug agreement and not the CBA, allowing Rodriguez to continue playing while the appeal was under way.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] The proposed suspension would include a global lock clause, which would also prevent him from playing in other known leagues, such as Nippon Professional Baseball and the Korea Baseball Championship, as the leagues in those nations honor any suspensions imposed by MLB.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Rodriguez hired New York criminal defense lawyer Joe Tacopina.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] A lengthy arbitration process followed, but the suspension was upheld on January 11, 2014.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] However, because Rodriguez was allowed to play during the appeal process, this effectively reduced the suspension to 162 games, the entirety of the 2014 regular-season schedule.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Because Rodriguez was on the suspended list retroactive through August 31, the suspension would have included the postseason if the Yankees had qualified, although the team failed to reach the playoffs.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Rodriguez issued a statement announcing that he would challenge the decision in federal court.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] On February 7, 2014, Rodriguez announced his decision to abandon his lawsuit and accept the suspension for the 2014 season.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] In March 2014, multiple sources reported that Rodriguez had refused to pay the balance of his legal fees, which amounted to more than $3 million.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] In July 2014, Rodriguez was sued by his lawyers for $380,000 in unpaid legal fees.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] In November 2014, it was revealed that in the previous January, Rodriguez had admitted to the Drug Enforcement Administration that he had used performance-enhancing drugs.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] This was contrary to his comments of 18 days earlier when he had vehemently refuted the allegations and denied having used human growth hormones.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Rodriguez founded A-Rod Corp, a holding company, in 1996 and the company began making its first investments in 2003.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Through the company, Rodriguez has invested in a series of companies in the technology, real estate, wellness, and entertainment industries.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] In 2008, Rodriguez founded Newport Property Construction, a real-estate development firm.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] In 2012, he founded Monument Capital Management, which has acquired more than $1 billion of real estate assets in 16 states.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] A-Rod Corp has invested in various companies including coconut water brand Vita Coco, Wheels Up, Snapchat, and virtual concert startup Wave.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Rodriguez partnered with Mark Mastrov in 2012 to create the Energy Fitness gym chain in Mexico City.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Rodriguez sold a Mercedes-Benz dealership in League City, Texas, to Group 1 Automotive in 2014.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Rodriguez invested in NRG Esports alongside Shaquille O'Neal and Jimmy Rollins in 2016.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] In 2017, A-Rod Corp gained the rights to develop UFC-branded fitness centers across southern Florida.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] That year, A-Rod Corp purchased a major equity stake in TruFusion, a Las Vegas-based fitness studio chain, and invested in the beverage brand Dirty Lemon.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] In 2018, A-Rod Corp invested in Petros Pace Finance, a financier of green development.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] In 2019, the company invested in the co-living startup Bungalow, Acorns and Sonder.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] That year, Rodriguez and Jennifer Lopez partnered with telehealth company Hims and Hers to provide affordable healthcare.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Rodriguez also invested in Density, a technology company specializing in people counting.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Rodriguez became the new chairman of Presidente, a Dominican beer company owned by Anheuser-Busch InBev, in January 2020.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] A-Rod Corp invested in Nova Credit, a financial technology company, in February 2020.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] In July 2020, Rodriguez and Lopez were leading a group of investors bidding on the New York Mets, and had moved to the second stage of the bidding process.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Rodriguez and Marc Lore agreed to purchase the Minnesota Timberwolves of the National Basketball Association in 2021.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Then-owner Glen Taylor said in 2024 that Rodriguez and Lore missed a payment to purchase the team, which was no longer for sale.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Rodriguez and Lore won an arbitration ruling in 2025 to allow them to purchase the team from Taylor.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] The purchase, valuing the team at $1.5 billion, was completed in June 2025.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Rodriguez partnered with Barstool Sports in 2018 to co-create *The Corp Podcast* with Dan Katz aka Barstool Big Cat.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] The podcast interviews industry leaders, athletes, and entrepreneurs.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Season 1 featured Kobe Bryant, Gary Vaynerchuk, Barbara Corcoran, Mike Francesa, Michael Rubin and Barry Sternlicht.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Season 2 featured Kevin Bacon, Martha Stewart, Danica Patrick, Stephanie McMahon, Maria Bartiromo, and Howard Schultz.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Rodriguez grew up with two half-siblings, Joe and Suzy, who were born in the Dominican Republic and are children from his mother's first marriage.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Rodriguez's father, Victor, left the family in Miami when Alex was nine years old and moved to New York.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] The next time that Alex heard from him, was the day of the 1993 MLB draft.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Rodriguez also has a half-brother, Victor M.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Rodriguez, who was born to Alex's father Victor Sr. and his then-wife Pouppe Martinez in 1960.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] The couple divorced a year later, and Victor Jr. grew up with his mother.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Victor Jr., who is an officer in the United States Air Force, fell out of touch with Alex for 23 years, until they met at a Texas Rangers game in 2003.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Alex's nephew, Joe Dunand, was a professional baseball player.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] In 2002, Alex Rodriguez and Cynthia Scurtis, a psychology graduate he had met at a gym in Miami, married.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Their first child was born on November 18, 2004.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] On April 21, 2008, Cynthia gave birth to their second child in Miami.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Cynthia Rodriguez filed for divorce on July 7, 2008, citing "emotional abandonment" of her and their children, "extramarital affairs and other marital misconduct" by her husband.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Alex responded in court documents that the marriage was "irretrievably broken" but requested that allegations of his "extramarital affairs" be stricken from court records.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] The couple reached a settlement that September.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] In July, Madonna responded to rumors of an affair with Alex releasing a statement saying, "I am not romantically involved in any way with Alex Rodriguez" and that she had "nothing to do with the state of his marriage".
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Alex dated Kate Hudson before having a relationship with Cameron Diaz from May 2010 to September 2011.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] He dated model, actress, and former WWE Diva Torrie Wilson from 2011 to 2014.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Then, he was in a short relationship with Anne Wojcicki, the founder of 23andMe, which ended in 2016 after dating for nearly a year.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] In February 2017, he and singer and actress Jennifer Lopez began dating.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] In March 2019, they announced their engagement.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] In a 2020 interview with Devin Banerjee, Rodriguez described Lopez as "a powerhouse" saying, "I've never met anyone who has the work ethic, the vision, the principles that Jennifer possesses.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] She does so many things that people call her a triple threat.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] I call her an octopus threat." In April 2021, he and Lopez announced the end of their engagement.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] In 2011, Rodriguez was represented by sports agent Dan Lozano.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] As of 2019, he is represented by Jon Rosen of WME/IMG.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] In 2003, Rodriguez gave $3.9 million to the University of Miami to renovate its baseball stadium.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] The new facility was renamed "Alex Rodriguez Park at Mark Light Field".
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Despite not having attended the school, he received the university's Edward T.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Foote II Alumnus of Distinction Award in 2007 as an honorary alumnus.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Rodriguez was named an "honorary alumnus" of the university in 2004.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] He is a member of the university's board of trustees.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] In 2017, Rodriguez and A-Rod Corp donated $500,000 to the university's School of Business Administration.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Rodriguez is a Miami-Dade Boys & Girls Clubs Board Member.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Rodriguez and A-Rod Corp donated $1 million to Boy & Girls Clubs of Miami-Dade in 2010, building a state-of-the-art educational center for students.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] He donated an additional $1 million to Boys & Girls Club in conjunction with MLB.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] In addition, Rodriguez created a scholarship program for Boys and Girls Club alumni to attend the University of Miami, sponsoring more than 25 students since inception of the program.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] In October 2019, Rodriguez, along with Jennifer Lopez, donated a year of prepared meals to Tennessee elementary students.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] In April 2020, Rodriguez and Lopez donated 20,000 prepared meals to help hospitality workers in the Miami area who had lost their jobs during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] He is also a member of the Paley Center for Media's board of trustees.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] Rodriguez was included on the ballot for the National Baseball Hall of Fame class of 2022 when it was announced on November 22, 2021.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] In his first three years of eligibility, his highest vote total is 35.7%.
[src:clutch-hitter/alex-rodriguez-p03] : Rodriguez hit 2 home runs as a DH in 2007.
[src:clutch-hitter/ball-boy] Quick retrieval of loose balls and delivery of the game balls to the servers are necessary for quick play in tennis.
[src:clutch-hitter/ball-boy] In professional tournaments, every court will have a trained squad of ball boys/girls with positionings and movements designed for maximum efficiency, while also not interfering with active play.
[src:clutch-hitter/ball-boy] As well as dealing with the game balls, ball boys/girls may also provide the players with other assistance, such as the delivery of towels and drinks.
[src:clutch-hitter/ball-boy] There are various methods for selecting the ball boys and girls for a tournament.
[src:clutch-hitter/ball-boy] In many tournaments, such as Wimbledon and the Queen's Club Championships, they are picked from or apply through schools, where they are selected by tournaments, and they have to go through a number of selections and tests.
[src:clutch-hitter/ball-boy] In some other tournaments, such as the Nottingham Open, Australian Open and the US Open, positions are advertised and there are open try-outs.
[src:clutch-hitter/ball-boy] Applicants are required to pass a physical ability assessment.
[src:clutch-hitter/ball-boy] In addition to fitness and stamina, the abilities to concentrate and remain alert are essential.
[src:clutch-hitter/ball-boy] In 2006, the IFAB Laws of the Game of association football were changed to allow multiple balls to be used under the direction of a referee.
[src:clutch-hitter/ball-boy] Higher level organised matches now commonly use 6+ balls with ball boys scattered around the pitch to quicken the pace of play.
[src:clutch-hitter/ball-boy] Typically positioned behind advertising boards surrounding the pitch, ball boys will try to be in possession of a spare ball at all times, so that this can be given to the players prior to the loose ball being retrieved.
[src:clutch-hitter/ball-boy] Balls may also be stored on cones near sidelines, so that they are readily available for restarts, and to prevent ball boys from accelerating returns to home players, and delaying returns to away players.
[src:clutch-hitter/ball-boy] Methods for selecting ball boys vary between grounds.
[src:clutch-hitter/ball-boy] On occasion, away teams have complained about perceived favour of ball boys towards home sides.
[src:clutch-hitter/ball-boy] In a 2013 EFL Cup match Eden Hazard, a member of the away team, which was trailing at the time, got into an altercation with an apparently time-wasting ball boy who was lying on top of the ball.
[src:clutch-hitter/ball-boy] Hazard was subsequently sent off for violent conduct and suspended for three games.
[src:clutch-hitter/ball-boy] Ball kids are stationed in out-of-play areas near the first and third base foul lines to retrieve out-of-play baseballs.
[src:clutch-hitter/ball-boy] They should not be confused with bat boys and bat girls, who remain in or near a team's dugout and the home plate area, primarily to tend to a team's baseball bats.
[src:clutch-hitter/ball-boy] As ball kids are stationed on the field, albeit in foul territory, they can occasionally interfere with play; such events are governed by Rule 6.01(d), the main point of which is that if the interference is unintentional, any live ball remains alive and in play.
[src:clutch-hitter/ball-boy] For this reason, most teams will use experienced individuals who understand the rules, to minimize mistaken interference.
[src:clutch-hitter/ball-boy] One of the more infamous examples was the use of a Hooters girl as a promotion.
[src:clutch-hitter/ball-boy] The woman unfortunately snagged a ball that was fair and live in a Tampa Bay Rays game, throwing it to the fans.
[src:clutch-hitter/ball-boy] The batter was awarded a double on the interference.
[src:clutch-hitter/ball-boy] Since 1992, the San Francisco Giants have employed older men as "balldudes", instead of the traditional youths.
[src:clutch-hitter/ball-boy] In 1993, Corinne Mullane became the first "balldudette", and she and her daughter Molly, who began working as a balldudette in the 2000s, have since been included in the National Baseball Hall of Fame as the first mother-daughter ball-retrieving duo in baseball.
[src:clutch-hitter/ball-boy] Ball boys are stationed around the field just outside the boundary to retrieve any balls struck into the spectator stands or to the boundary rope.
[src:clutch-hitter/ball-boy] In India, disabled people are not allowed to be ball-boys anymore after a controversy occurred in 2017, after criticism of the Board of Control for Cricket in India surrounding the appearance of a polio-afflicted fan who had been serving as a ball-boy for a few years.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] In baseball, **base running** is the act of running from base to base, performed by members of the team at bat.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] Base running is a tactical part of the game with the goal of eventually reaching home base (home plate) to score a run.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] Batters strive to become base runners, and to enable existing base runners to move to a subsequent base or to score.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] In statistics, the number of baserunners (for example those allowed by a pitcher) is denoted by the abbreviation **BR**.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] The Official Baseball Rules uses the term **batter-runner** to identify the batter from the time he becomes a base runner until the end of the same play, whether he is successful at legally attaining first base or any subsequent base.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] The term is not applied if the batter is awarded first base (the last three items in the above list).
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] If a base runner's teammate is put out for the third out of the inning, the base runner is said to be left on base (LOB).
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] A runner who is touching a base which he is entitled to occupy may not be tagged out.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] Runners may attempt to advance from base to base on any fair ball that touches the ground.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] When a ball is hit in the air (i.e., a *fly ball*) and caught by the defending team, runners must return and touch the base they occupy—called *tagging up*—after the ball is first touched by a fielder.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] Once they do this, they may attempt to advance at their own risk.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] On a ball that touches the ground in fair territory, if there is a force, runners are required to run.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] Base runners may attempt to advance at any time while the ball is alive, even before or while the pitcher is throwing a pitch.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] The catcher—or pitcher, in lieu of delivering the pitch—often tries to prevent this by throwing the ball to one of the infielders in order to tag the runner.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] This *pick-off attempt* is usually unsuccessful in tagging out the runner but is effective in keeping the runner closer to the base.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] If the runner is tagged out while diving back to the base, it is called a *pickoff*.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] If the runner attempts to advance to the next base but is tagged out before reaching it safely, he is *caught stealing*.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] A successful attempt by the runner is called a *stolen base*.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] If a pitch gets away from the catcher, runners may also try to advance.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] This may be a *wild pitch*, if the pitcher is held responsible for the ball getting away, or a *passed ball* if the catcher is deemed to be at fault.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] Sometimes the defending team will ignore a runner who is trying to steal a base; in this case a runner is not credited with a steal, and the base is attributed to *defensive indifference*.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] An infielder who cleanly fields a ball hit on the ground, then throws it quickly and accurately, will usually get the ball to a base before the runner runs the 90 feet (27 m).
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] However, any hesitation or mistake on the part of the fielder may allow the runner to reach the base safely.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] Teams scout the opposition and take advantage of players who are poor at defense.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] For example, on a deep fly ball to center field with a man on second base, if the center fielder has a weak arm, the runner on second base may tag the base and attempt to reach third despite the risks of being tagged out.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] Base running and hitting are coordinated to produce better results in the squeeze play and the hit and run play.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] When the count is full and there are two outs, any runners forced to advance begin running as soon as the pitcher's motion obliges him to complete his pitch, as their distance from the base will not be the cause of any third out.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] Good runners also try to get extra bases when a play is being made at a different base.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] For example, a batter who hits a single should determine whether the defense's focus on another runner gives the batter a chance to reach second base.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] Sliding into a base is an important part of base running.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] The pop-up slide both ensures that the runner touches the base and elevates him to an upright posture to help him take additional bases if the defense misperforms.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] A take-out slide tries to use a collision with a fielder to keep him from taking additional action, such as throwing to achieve a double play.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] However, this move, when made independently of the attempt to reach the base, has been illegal since 2016 because of the potential for injury.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] The base coach at third base, and any batter still at home plate, may watch the ball approaching the base and may signal the base runner on the optimum slide to avoid being tagged out.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] The most baserunners allowed by a pitcher in a game since 1901 is 39, by Eddie Rommel, who pitched 17 innings in relief for the Philadelphia Athletics to defeat the Cleveland Indians, 18–17, on July 10, 1932.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] The record number of baserunners in a season is 820, by John Coleman of the Philadelphia Quakers in 1883.
[src:clutch-hitter/base-running] Wilbur Wood of the 1973 Chicago White Sox was the last pitcher to allow more than 500 baserunners in a season.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] In 2006, *Time* named him in the *Time* 100 as one of the most influential people in the world.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] In 2003, James was hired as senior advisor on Baseball Operations for the Boston Red Sox and worked for the team for 17 years during which they won four World Series championships.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] He joined the United States Army in 1971.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] After his service, he graduated from the University of Kansas in 1973 with degrees in English and economics, and in 1975 with a degree in education.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] An aspiring writer and obsessive fan, James began writing baseball articles in his mid-twenties after leaving the United States Army.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] Many of his first baseball writings came while he was doing night shifts as a security guard at the Stokely-Van Camp's pork and beans cannery.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] Unlike most writers, his pieces did not recount games in epic terms or offer insights gleaned from interviews with players.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] A typical James piece posed a question (*e.g.,* "Which pitchers and catchers allow runners to steal the most bases?"), and then presented data and analysis that offered an answer.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] Editors considered James's pieces so unusual that few believed them suitable for their readers.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] In an effort to reach a wider audience, James began self-publishing an annual book titled *The Bill James Baseball Abstract*, beginning in 1977.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] Seventy-five people purchased the booklet.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] The 1978 edition, subtitled *The 2nd annual edition of baseball's most informative and imaginative review*, sold 250 copies.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] Beginning in 1979, James wrote an annual preview of the baseball season for *Esquire*, and continued to do so through 1984.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] The first three editions of the *Baseball Abstract* garnered respect for James's work, including a very favorable review by Daniel Okrent in *Sports Illustrated*.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] New annual editions added essays on teams and players.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] By 1982 sales had increased tenfold, and a media conglomerate agreed to publish and distribute future editions.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] While writers had published books about baseball statistics before (most notably Earnshaw Cook's *Percentage Baseball*, in the 1960s), few had ever reached a mass audience.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] Attempts to imitate James's work spawned a flood of books and articles that continues to this day.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] In 1988, James ceased writing the *Abstract*, citing workload-related burnout and concern about the volume of statistics on the market.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] He has continued to publish hardcover books about baseball history, which have sold well and received admiring reviews.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] These books include three editions of *The Bill James Historical Baseball Abstract* (1985, 1988, 2001, the last entitled *The New Bill James Historical Baseball Abstract*).
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] In 2008, James launched Bill James Online.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] Subscribers could read James's new, original writing and interact with one another—as well as with James—in a question-and-answer format.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] The web site also offered new "profiles" of teams and players full of facts and statistics that hoped to map what James has termed "the lost island of baseball statistics".
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] On June 9, 2023, James wrote an article for the site announcing that it would soon be closed in order for James to "focus on other projects".
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] In an essay published in the 1984 *Abstract*, James vented his frustration about Major League Baseball's refusal to publish play-by-play accounts of every game.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] James proposed the creation of Project Scoresheet, a network of fans that would work together to collect and distribute this information.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] While the resulting non-profit organization never functioned smoothly, it worked well enough to collect accounts of every game from 1984 through 1991.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] James's publisher agreed to distribute two annuals of essays and data—the 1987 and 1988 editions of *Bill James Presents The Great American Baseball Statbook* (though only the first of these featured writing by James).
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] The organization was eventually disbanded, but many of its members went on to form for-profit companies with similar goals and structure.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] STATS, Inc., the company James joined, provided data and analysis to every major media outlet before being acquired by Fox Sports in 2001.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] Although James may be best known as an inventor of statistical tools, he has often written on the limitations of statistics and urged humility concerning their place amid other kinds of information about baseball.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] To James, context is paramount: he was among the first to emphasize the importance of adjusting traditional statistics for park factors and to stress the role of luck in a pitcher's win–loss record.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] Many of his statistical innovations are arguably less important than the underlying ideas.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] When he introduced the notion of secondary average, it was as a vehicle for the then-counterintuitive concept that batting average represents only a fraction of a player's offensive contribution.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] (The runs-created statistic plays a similar role vis-à-vis the traditional RBI.) Some of his contributions to the language of baseball, like the idea of the "defensive spectrum", border on being entirely non-statistical.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] Oakland Athletics general manager Billy Beane began applying sabermetric principles to running his low-budget team in the early 2000s, to notable effect, as chronicled in Michael Lewis' book *Moneyball*.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] In 2003, James was hired by a former reader, John Henry, the new owner of the Boston Red Sox.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] One point of controversy was in handling the relief pitching of the Red Sox.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] James had previously published analysis of the use of the closer in baseball, and had concluded that the traditional use of the closer both overrated the abilities of that individual and used him in suboptimal circumstances.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] He wrote that it is "far better to use your relief ace when the score is tied, even if that is the seventh inning, than in the ninth inning with a lead of two or more runs." The Red Sox in 2003 staffed their bullpen with several marginally talented relievers.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] Red Sox manager Grady Little was never fully comfortable with the setup, and designated unofficial closers and reshuffled roles after a bad outing.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] When Boston lost a number of games due to bullpen failures, Little reverted to a traditional closer approach and moved Byung-hyun Kim from being a starting pitcher to a closer.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] The Red Sox did not follow James's idea of a bullpen with no closer, but with consistent overall talent that would allow the responsibilities to be shared.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] Red Sox reliever Alan Embree thought the plan could have worked if the bullpen had not suffered injuries.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] During the 2004 regular season Keith Foulke was used primarily as a closer in the conventional model; however, Foulke's usage in the 2004 postseason was along the lines of a relief ace with multiple inning appearances at pivotal times of the game.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] Houston Astros manager Phil Garner also employed a relief ace model with his use of Brad Lidge in the 2004 postseason.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] During his tenure with the Red Sox, James published several new sabermetric books (see #Bibliography below).
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] After the Red Sox suffered through a disastrous 2012 season, Henry stated that James had fallen "out of favor [in the front office] over the last few years for reasons I really don't understand.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] On October 24, 2019, James announced his retirement from the Red Sox, saying that he had "fallen out of step with the organization" and added that he hadn't earned his paycheck with the Red Sox for the last couple of years.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] During his time with the team, Bill James received four World Series rings for the team's 2004, 2007, 2013, and 2018 World Series titles.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] James has written two true crime books, *Popular Crime: Reflections on the Celebration of Violence* (2011) and – together with his daughter Rachel McCarthy James – *The Man from the Train* (2017).
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] The latter is an attempt to link scores of murders of entire families in the early 20th century United States to a single perpetrator.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] Those murders include the Villisca axe murders.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] The Jameses propose a solution to the murders based on the signature elements these killings share with each other.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] James is a fan of the University of Kansas men's basketball team and has written about basketball.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] He has created a formula for what he calls a "safe lead" in the sport.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] Michael Lewis, in his 2003 book *Moneyball*, dedicates a chapter to James's career and sabermetrics as background for his portrayal of Billy Beane and the Oakland Athletics' unlikely success.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] James was inducted into the Baseball Reliquary's Shrine of the Eternals in 2007.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] James was profiled on *60 Minutes* on March 30, 2008, in his role as a sabermetric pioneer and Red Sox advisor.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] In 2010, he was inducted into the Irish American Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] James made a guest appearance on *The Simpsons* 2010 episode "MoneyBART".
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] Steven Soderbergh's planned film adaptation of *Moneyball* would have featured an animated version of James as a "host".
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] This script was discarded when director Bennett Miller and writer Aaron Sorkin succeeded Soderbergh on the project.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] Ultimately, the 2011 film mentions James several times.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] His bio is briefly recapped, and Billy Beane is depicted telling John Henry that Henry's hiring of James is the reason Beane is interested in the Red Sox general manager job.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] In his *Baseball Book 1990*, James heavily criticized the methodology of the Dowd Report, which was an investigation (commissioned by baseball commissioner Bart Giamatti) on the gambling activities of Pete Rose.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] James reproached commissioner Giamatti and his successor, Fay Vincent, for their acceptance of the Dowd Report as the final word on Rose's gambling.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] James expanded his defense of Rose in his 2001 book *The New Historical Baseball Abstract*, with a detailed explanation of why he found the case against Rose flimsy.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] James wrote "I would characterize the evidence that Rose bet on baseball as... well, not quite non-existent.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] It is extremely weak." This countered the popular opinion that the case against Rose was a slam dunk, and several critics claimed James misstated some of the evidence in his defense of Rose.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] In 2004, Rose admitted publicly he had bet on baseball and confirmed the Dowd Report was correct.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] James remained steadfast, continuing to insist that the evidence available to Dowd at the time was insufficient to reach the conclusion that it did.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] On November 4, 2011, Jerry Sandusky was indicted for committing sex crimes against young boys, which brought the Penn State child sex abuse scandal to national attention.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] On July 12, 2012, the Freeh report was released, charging Paterno and three other University officials with covering up reports of sexual assaults and enabling the attacker to prey on other children for more than a decade, often in Pennsylvania State University facilities.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] Soon afterwards, during an interview on ESPN radio, James claimed that the Freeh report's characterizations of Paterno as a powerful figure were wrong, and that it was not Paterno's responsibility to report allegations of child molestation to the police.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] He was isolated and he was not nearly as powerful as people imagine him to have been." When asked if he knew anyone who had showered with a boy they were not related to, James said it was a common practice when he was growing up.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] "That was actually quite common in the town I grew up in.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] The July 2012 interview comments were widely criticized.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] James's employer, the Boston Red Sox, issued a statement disavowing the comments James made and saying that he had been asked not to make further public comments on the matter.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] On November 7, 2018, James participated in a Twitter conversation regarding comments made by agent Scott Boras about teams "tanking".
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] This was arguably consistent with thoughts James had publicly expressed prior to his affiliation with the Red Sox.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] Nonetheless, in the context of James's association with the Red Sox front office and baseball's checkered labor history (including alleged collusion amongst the owners in the previous offseason to curb free agent salaries), the tweets were taken by many as inflammatory.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] Major League Baseball Players Association executive director Tony Clark called James's comments "reckless and insulting".
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] Other active or former players also objected.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-abstract] In January 2024, James announced that he had suffered a stroke, which impeded the use of his right hand.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The initial objective of the batting team is to have a player reach first base safely; this occurs either when the batter hits the ball and reaches first base before an opponent retrieves the ball and touches the base, or when the pitcher persists in throwing the ball out of the batter's reach.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Players on the batting team who reach first base without being called "out" can attempt to advance to subsequent bases as a runner, either immediately or during teammates' turns batting.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The fielding team tries to prevent runs by using the ball to get batters or runners "out", which forces them out of the field of play.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The pitcher can get the batter out by throwing three pitches which result in strikes, while fielders can get the batter out by catching a batted ball before it touches the ground, and can get a runner out by tagging them with the ball while the runner is not touching a base.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The opposing teams switch back and forth between batting and fielding; the batting team's turn to bat is over once the fielding team records three outs.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] One turn batting for each team constitutes an inning.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] A game is usually composed of nine innings, and the team with the greater number of runs at the end of the game wins.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Most games end after the ninth inning, but if scores are tied at that point, extra innings are usually played.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Baseball has no game clock, though some competitions feature pace-of-play regulations such as a pitch clock to shorten game time.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Baseball evolved from older bat-and-ball games already being played in England by the mid-18th century.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] This game was brought by immigrants to North America, where the modern version developed.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In addition to North America, baseball spread throughout the rest of the Americas and the Asia–Pacific in the 19th and 20th centuries, and is now considered the most popular sport in parts of Central and South America, the Caribbean, and East Asia, particularly in Japan, South Korea, and Taiwan.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In Major League Baseball (MLB), the highest level of professional baseball in the United States and Canada, teams are divided into the National League (NL) and American League (AL), each with three divisions: East, West, and Central.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The MLB champion is determined by playoffs that culminate in the World Series.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The top level of play is similarly split in Japan between the Central and Pacific Leagues and in Cuba between the West League and East League.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The World Baseball Classic, organized by the World Baseball Softball Confederation, is the major international competition of the sport and attracts the top national teams from around the world.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Baseball was played at the Olympic Games from 1992 to 2008, and was reinstated on a one-off basis in 2020.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] A baseball game is played between two teams, each composed of nine players, that take turns playing offense (batting and baserunning) and defense (pitching and fielding).
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] A pair of turns, one at bat and one in the field, by each team constitutes an inning.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] A game consists of nine innings (seven innings at the high school level and in doubleheaders in college and Minor League Baseball; and six innings at the Little League level).
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] One team—customarily the visiting team—bats in the top, or first half, of every inning.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The other team—customarily the home team—bats in the bottom, or second half, of every inning.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The goal of the game is to score more points (runs) than the other team.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The players on the team at bat attempt to score runs by touching all four bases, in order, set at the corners of the square-shaped baseball diamond.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] A player bats at home plate and must attempt to safely reach a base before proceeding, counterclockwise, from first base, to second base, third base, and back home to score a run.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The team in the field attempts to prevent runs from scoring by recording outs, which remove opposing players from offensive action until their next turn at bat comes up again.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] When three outs are recorded, the teams switch roles for the next half-inning.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] If the score of the game is tied after nine innings, extra innings are played to resolve the contest.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Many amateur games, particularly unorganized ones, involve different numbers of players and innings.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The game is played on a field whose primary boundaries, the foul lines, extend forward from home plate at 45-degree angles.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The 90-degree area within the foul lines is referred to as fair territory; the 270-degree area outside them is foul territory.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The part of the field enclosed by the bases and several yards beyond them is the infield; the area farther beyond the infield is the outfield.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In the middle of the infield is a raised pitcher's mound, with a rectangular rubber plate (the rubber) at its center.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The outer boundary of the outfield is typically demarcated by a raised fence, which may be of any material and height.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The fair territory between home plate and the outfield boundary is baseball's field of play, though significant events can take place in foul territory, as well.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Protective helmets are also standard equipment for all batters.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] At the beginning of each half-inning, the nine players of the fielding team arrange themselves around the field.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] One of them, the pitcher, stands on the pitcher's mound.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The pitcher begins the pitching delivery with one foot on the rubber, pushing off it to gain velocity when throwing toward home plate.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Another fielding team player, the catcher, squats on the far side of home plate, facing the pitcher.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The rest of the fielding team faces home plate, typically arranged as four infielders—who set up along or within a few yards outside the imaginary lines (basepaths) between first, second, and third base—and three outfielders.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In the standard arrangement, there is a first baseman positioned several steps to the left of first base, a second baseman to the right of second base, a shortstop to the left of second base, and a third baseman to the right of third base.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The basic outfield positions are left fielder, center fielder, and right fielder.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] With the exception of the catcher, all fielders are required to be in fair territory when the pitch is delivered.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] A neutral umpire sets up behind the catcher.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Other umpires will be distributed around the field as well.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Play starts with a member of the batting team, the batter, standing in either of the two batter's boxes next to home plate, holding a bat.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The batter waits for the pitcher to throw a pitch (the ball) toward home plate, and attempts to hit the ball with the bat.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The catcher catches pitches that the batter does not hit—as a result of either electing not to swing or failing to connect—and returns them to the pitcher.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] A batter who hits the ball into the field of play must drop the bat and begin running toward first base, at which point the player is referred to as a *runner* (or, until the play is over, a *batter-runner*).
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] A batter-runner who reaches first base without being put out is said to be *safe* and is on base.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] A batter-runner may choose to remain at first base or attempt to advance to second base or even beyond—however far the player believes can be reached safely.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base despite proper play by the fielders has recorded a hit.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] A player who reaches first base safely on a hit is credited with a single.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] If a player makes it to second base safely as a direct result of a hit, it is a double; third base, a triple.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air within the foul lines over the entire outfield (and outfield fence, if there is one), or if the batter-runner otherwise safely circles all the bases, it is a home run: the batter and any runners on base may all freely circle the bases, each scoring a run.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] This is the most desirable result for the batter.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The ultimate and most desirable result possible for a batter would be to hit a home run while all three bases are occupied or "loaded", thus scoring four runs on a single hit.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base due to a fielding mistake is not credited with a hit—instead, the responsible fielder is charged with an error.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Any runners already on base may attempt to advance on batted balls that land, or contact the ground, in fair territory, before or after the ball lands.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] A runner on first base *must* attempt to advance if a ball lands in play, as only one runner may occupy a base at any given time; the same applies for other runners if they are on a base that a teammate is forced to advance to.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] If a ball hit into play rolls foul before passing through the infield, it becomes dead and any runners must return to the base they occupied when the play began.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air and caught before it lands, the batter has flied out and any runners on base may attempt to advance only if they tag up (contact the base they occupied when the play began, as or after the ball is caught).
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Runners may also attempt to advance to the next base while the pitcher is in the process of delivering the ball to home plate; a successful effort is a stolen base.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] A pitch that is not hit into the field of play is called either a strike or a ball.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] A batter against whom three strikes are recorded strikes out.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] A batter against whom four balls are recorded is awarded a base on balls or walk, a free advance to first base.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] While the team at bat is trying to score runs, the team in the field is attempting to record outs.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In addition to the strikeout and flyout, common ways a member of the batting team may be put out include the ground out, force out, and tag out.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] These occur either when a runner is forced to advance to a base, and a fielder with possession of the ball reaches that base before the runner does, or the runner is touched by the ball, held in a fielder's hand, while not on a base.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] (The batter-runner is always forced to advance to first base, and any other runners must advance to the next base if a teammate is forced to advance to their base.) It is possible to record two outs in the course of the same play.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Three outs in one play, a triple play, is possible, though rare.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Players put out or retired must leave the field, returning to their team's dugout or bench.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] A runner may be stranded on base when a third out is recorded against another player on the team.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Stranded runners do not benefit the team in its next turn at bat as every half-inning begins with the bases empty.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] An individual player's turn batting or plate appearance is complete when the player reaches base, hits a home run, makes an out, or hits a ball that results in the team's third out, even if it is recorded against a teammate.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] On rare occasions, a batter may be at the plate when, without the batter's hitting the ball, a third out is recorded against a teammate—for instance, a runner getting caught stealing (tagged out attempting to steal a base).
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] A batter with this sort of incomplete plate appearance starts off the team's next turn batting; any balls or strikes recorded against the batter the previous inning are erased.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] A runner may circle the bases only once per plate appearance and thus can score at most a single run per batting turn.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Once a player has completed a plate appearance, that player may not bat again until the eight other members of the player's team have all taken their turn at bat in the batting order.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The batting order is set before the game begins, and may not be altered except for substitutions.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Once a player has been removed for a substitute, that player may not reenter the game.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Children's games often have more lenient rules, such as Little League rules, which allow players to be substituted back into the same game.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] If the designated hitter (DH) rule is in effect, each team has a tenth player whose sole responsibility is to bat (and run).
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The DH takes the place of another player—almost invariably the pitcher—in the batting order, but does not field.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Thus, even with the DH, each team still has a batting order of nine players and a fielding arrangement of nine players.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The number of players on a baseball roster, or *squad*, varies by league and by the level of organized play.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] A Major League Baseball (MLB) team has a roster of 26 players with specific roles.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Most baseball leagues worldwide have the DH rule, including MLB, Japan's Pacific League, and Caribbean professional leagues, along with major American amateur organizations.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The Central League in Japan does not have the rule and high-level minor league clubs connected to National League teams are not required to field a DH.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In leagues that apply the designated hitter rule, a typical team has nine offensive regulars (including the DH), five starting pitchers, seven or eight relievers, a backup catcher, and two or three other reserve players.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The manager, or head coach, oversees the team's major strategic decisions, such as establishing the starting rotation, setting the lineup, or batting order, before each game, and making substitutions during games—in particular, bringing in relief pitchers.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Managers are typically assisted by two or more coaches; they may have specialized responsibilities, such as working with players on hitting, fielding, pitching, or strength and conditioning.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] At most levels of organized play, two coaches are stationed on the field when the team is at bat: the first base coach and third base coach, who occupy designated coaches' boxes, just outside the foul lines.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] These coaches assist in the direction of baserunners, when the ball is in play, and relay tactical signals from the manager to batters and runners, during pauses in play.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In contrast to many other team sports, baseball managers and coaches generally wear their team's uniforms; coaches must be in uniform to be allowed on the field to confer with players during a game.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Any baseball game involves one or more umpires, who make rulings on the outcome of each play.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] At a minimum, one umpire will stand behind the catcher, to have a good view of the strike zone, and call balls and strikes.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Additional umpires may be stationed near the other bases, thus making it easier to judge plays such as attempted force outs and tag outs.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In MLB, four umpires are used for each game, one near each base.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In the playoffs, six umpires are used: one at each base and two in the outfield along the foul lines.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Many of the pre-game and in-game strategic decisions in baseball revolve around a fundamental fact: in general, right-handed batters tend to be more successful against left-handed pitchers and, to an even greater degree, left-handed batters tend to be more successful against right-handed pitchers.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] A manager with several left-handed batters in the regular lineup, who knows the team will be facing a left-handed starting pitcher, may respond by starting one or more of the right-handed backups on the team's roster.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] During the late innings of a game, as relief pitchers and pinch hitters are brought in, the opposing managers will often go back and forth trying to create favorable matchups with their substitutions.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The manager of the fielding team trying to arrange same-handed pitcher-batter matchups and the manager of the batting team trying to arrange opposite-handed matchups.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] With a team that has the lead in the late innings, a manager may remove a starting position player—especially one whose turn at bat is not likely to come up again—for a more skillful fielder (known as a defensive substitution).
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The tactical decision that precedes almost every play in a baseball game involves pitch selection.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] By gripping and then releasing the baseball in a certain manner, and by throwing it at a certain speed, pitchers can cause the baseball to break to either side, or downward, as it approaches the batter, thus creating differing pitches that can be selected.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Among the resulting wide variety of pitches that may be thrown, the four basic types are the fastball, the changeup (or off-speed pitch), and two breaking balls—the curveball and the slider.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Pitchers have different repertoires of pitches they are skillful at throwing.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Conventionally, before each pitch, the catcher signals the pitcher what type of pitch to throw, as well as its general vertical or horizontal location.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] If there is disagreement on the selection, the pitcher may shake off the sign and the catcher will call for a different pitch.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] With a runner on base and taking a lead, the pitcher may attempt a pickoff, a quick throw to a fielder covering the base to keep the runner's lead in check or, optimally, effect a tag out.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Pickoff attempts, however, are subject to rules that severely restrict the pitcher's movements before and during the pickoff attempt.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Violation of any one of these rules could result in the umpire calling a balk against the pitcher, which permits any runners on base to advance one base with impunity.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] If an attempted stolen base is anticipated, the catcher may call for a pitchout, a ball thrown deliberately off the plate, allowing the catcher to catch it while standing and throw quickly to a base.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Facing a batter with a strong tendency to hit to one side of the field, the fielding team may employ a shift, with most or all of the fielders moving to the left or right of their usual positions.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] With a runner on third base, the infielders may play in, moving closer to home plate to improve the odds of throwing out the runner on a ground ball, though a sharply hit grounder is more likely to carry through a drawn-in infield.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Several basic offensive tactics come into play with a runner on first base, including the fundamental choice of whether to attempt a steal of second base.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The hit and run is sometimes employed, with a skillful contact hitter, the runner takes off with the pitch, drawing the shortstop or second baseman over to second base, creating a gap in the infield for the batter to poke the ball through.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The sacrifice bunt, calls for the batter to focus on making soft contact with the ball, so that it rolls a short distance into the infield, allowing the runner to advance into scoring position as the batter is thrown out at first.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] A batter, particularly one who is a fast runner, may also attempt to bunt for a hit.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] A sacrifice bunt employed with a runner on third base, aimed at bringing that runner home, is known as a squeeze play.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] With a runner on third and fewer than two outs, a batter may instead concentrate on hitting a fly ball that, even if it is caught, will be deep enough to allow the runner to tag up and score—a successful batter, in this case, gets credit for a sacrifice fly.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In order to increase the chance of advancing a batter to first base via a walk, the manager will sometimes signal a batter who is ahead in the count (i.e., has more balls than strikes) to take, or not swing at, the next pitch.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The batter's potential reward of reaching base (via a walk) exceeds the disadvantage if the next pitch is a strike.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Consensus once held that today's baseball is a North American development from the older game rounders, popular among children in Great Britain and Ireland.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] American baseball historian David Block suggests that the game originated in England; recently uncovered historical evidence supports this position.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] According to Block and official MLB historian John Thorn, this earlier version of baseball may have involved hitting the ball with a hand, making it akin to today's punchball.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Block argues that rounders and early baseball were actually regional variants of each other, and that the game's most direct antecedents are the English games of stoolball and "tut-ball".
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The earliest known reference to baseball is in a 1744 British publication, *A Little Pretty Pocket-Book*, by John Newbery.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Block discovered that the first recorded game of "Base Ball" took place in 1749 in Surrey, and featured the Prince of Wales as a player.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] This early form of the game was apparently brought to Canada by English immigrants.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] By the early 1830s, there were reports of a variety of uncodified bat-and-ball games recognizable as early forms of baseball being played around North America.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The first recorded baseball game in North America was played in Beachville, Ontario, Canada, on June 4, 1838.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In 1845, Alexander Cartwright, a member of New York City's Knickerbocker Club, led the codification of the so-called Knickerbocker Rules, which in turn were based on rules developed in 1837 by William R.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] While there are reports that the New York Knickerbockers played games in 1845, the contest long recognized as the first recorded baseball game in U.S. history took place on June 19, 1846, in Hoboken, New Jersey: the "New York Nine" defeated the Knickerbockers, 23–1, in four innings.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] With the Knickerbocker code as the basis, the rules of modern baseball continued to evolve over the next half-century.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The game then went on to spread throughout the Pacific Rim and the Americas, with Americans backing the sport as a way to spread American values.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In the mid-1850s, a baseball craze hit the New York metropolitan area, and by 1856, local journals were referring to baseball as the "national pastime" or "national game".
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] A year later, the sport's first governing body, the National Association of Base Ball Players, was formed.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In 1867, it barred participation by African Americans.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The more formally structured National League was founded in 1876.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Professional Negro leagues formed, but quickly folded.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In 1887, softball, under the name of indoor baseball or indoor-outdoor, was invented as a winter version of the parent game.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The American League evolved from the minor Western League, which was reorganized under Ban Johnson in 1893.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] It was not until 1901 that the American League was formally established as a major league.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] By 1893, crucial structural changes (like moving the pitching distance to 60 feet, 6 inches) firmly cemented the modern rulebook.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The National Agreement of 1903 formalized relations both between the two major leagues and between them and the National Association of Professional Base Ball Leagues, representing most of the country's minor professional leagues.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The World Series, pitting the two major league champions against each other, was inaugurated that fall.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The Black Sox Scandal of the 1919 World Series led to the formation of the office of the Commissioner of Baseball.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The first commissioner, Kenesaw Mountain Landis, was elected in 1920.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] That year also saw the founding of the Negro National League; the first significant Negro league, it would operate until 1931.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] For part of the 1920s, it was joined by the Eastern Colored League.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Compared with the present, professional baseball in the early 20th century was lower-scoring, and pitchers were more dominant.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] This so-called "dead-ball era" ended in the early 1920s with several changes in rule and circumstance that were advantageous to hitters.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Strict new regulations that governed the ball's size, shape and composition, along with a new rule officially banning the spitball and other pitches that depended on the ball being treated or roughed-up with foreign substances, resulted in a ball that traveled farther when hit.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The rise of the legendary player Babe Ruth, the first great power hitter of the new era, helped permanently alter the nature of the game.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Louis Cardinals general manager Branch Rickey invested in several minor league clubs and developed the first modern farm system.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] A new Negro National League was organized in 1933; four years later, it was joined by the Negro American League.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The first elections to the National Baseball Hall of Fame took place in 1936.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In 1939, Little League Baseball was founded in Pennsylvania.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Many minor league teams disbanded when World War II led to a player shortage.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Wrigley led the formation of the All-American Girls Professional Baseball League to help keep the game in the public eye.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The first crack in the unwritten agreement barring blacks from white-controlled professional ball occurred in 1945: Jackie Robinson was signed by the National League's Brooklyn Dodgers and began playing for their minor league team in Montreal.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In 1947, Robinson broke the major leagues' color barrier when he debuted with the Dodgers.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Latin-American players, largely overlooked before, also started entering the majors in greater numbers.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In 1951, two Chicago White Sox, Venezuelan-born Chico Carrasquel and black Cuban-born Minnie Miñoso, became the first Hispanic All-Stars.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Integration proceeded slowly: by 1953, only six of the 16 major league teams had a black player on the roster.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In 1975, the union's power—and players' salaries—began to increase greatly when the reserve clause was effectively struck down, leading to the free agency system.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Significant work stoppages occurred in 1981 and 1994, the latter forcing the cancellation of the World Series for the first time in 90 years.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Attendance had been growing steadily since the mid-1970s and in 1994, before the stoppage, the majors were setting their all-time record for per-game attendance.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] After play resumed in 1995, non-division-winning wild card teams became a permanent fixture of the post-season.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Regular-season interleague play was introduced in 1997 and the second-highest attendance mark for a full season was set.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In 2000, the National and American Leagues were dissolved as legal entities.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] While their identities were maintained for scheduling purposes (and the designated hitter distinction), the regulations and other functions—such as player discipline and umpire supervision—they had administered separately were consolidated under the rubric of MLB.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In 2001, Barry Bonds established the current record of 73 home runs in a single season.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In 2007, Bonds became MLB's all-time home run leader, surpassing Hank Aaron, as total major league and minor league attendance both reached all-time highs.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Despite having been called "America's national pastime", baseball is well-established in several other countries.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] As early as 1877, a professional league, the International Association, featured teams from both Canada and the United States.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] While baseball is widely played in Canada and many minor league teams have been based in the country, the American major leagues did not include a Canadian club until 1969, when the Montreal Expos joined the National League as an expansion team.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In 1977, the expansion Toronto Blue Jays joined the American League.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In 1847, American soldiers played what may have been the first baseball game in Mexico at Parque Los Berros in Xalapa, Veracruz.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The first formal baseball league outside of the United States and Canada was founded in 1878 in Cuba, which maintains a rich baseball tradition.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The English football club, Aston Villa, were the first British baseball champions winning the 1890 National League of Baseball of Great Britain.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The 2025 National Champions were the London Mets.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The Dominican Republic held its first islandwide championship tournament in 1912.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Professional baseball tournaments and leagues began to form in other countries between the world wars, including the Netherlands (formed in 1922), Australia (1934), Japan (1936), Mexico (1937), and Puerto Rico (1938).
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The Japanese major leagues have long been considered the highest quality professional circuits outside of the United States.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] After World War II, professional leagues were founded in many Latin American countries, most prominently Venezuela (1946) and the Dominican Republic (1955).
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Since the early 1970s, the annual Caribbean Series has matched the championship clubs from the four leading Latin American winter leagues: the Dominican Professional Baseball League, Mexican Pacific League, Puerto Rican Professional Baseball League, and Venezuelan Professional Baseball League.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In Asia, South Korea (1982), Taiwan (1990) and China (2003) all have professional leagues.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Other European countries have seen professional leagues; the most successful, other than the Dutch league, is the Italian league, founded in 1948.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In 2004, Australia won a surprise silver medal at the Olympic Games.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The Confédération Européene de Baseball (European Baseball Confederation), founded in 1953, organizes a number of competitions between clubs from different countries.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Women's baseball is played on an organized amateur basis in numerous countries.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] After being admitted to the Olympics as a medal sport beginning with the 1992 Games, baseball was dropped from the 2012 Summer Olympic Games at the 2005 International Olympic Committee meeting.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] While the sport's lack of a following in much of the world was a factor, more important was MLB's reluctance to allow its players to participate during the major league season.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] MLB initiated the World Baseball Classic, scheduled to precede its season, partly as a replacement, high-profile international tournament.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The inaugural Classic, held in March 2006, was the first tournament involving national teams to feature a significant number of MLB participants.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The Baseball World Cup was discontinued after its 2011 edition in favor of an expanded World Baseball Classic.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Baseball has certain attributes that set it apart from the other popular team sports in the countries where it has a following.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] All of these sports use a clock, play is less individual, and the variation between playing fields is not as substantial or important.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The comparison between cricket and baseball demonstrates that many of baseball's distinctive elements are shared in various ways with similar sports.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In clock-limited sports, games often end with a team that holds the lead killing the clock rather than competing aggressively against the opposing team.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In contrast, baseball has no clock, thus a team cannot win without getting the last batter out and rallies are not constrained by time.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] At almost any turn in any baseball game, the most advantageous strategy is some form of aggressive strategy.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] While nine innings has been the standard since the beginning of professional baseball, the duration of the average major league game has increased steadily through the years.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] At the turn of the 20th century, games typically took an hour and a half to play.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In the 1920s, they averaged just less than two hours, which eventually ballooned to 2:38 in 1960.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] By 1997, the average American League game lasted 2:57 (National League games were about 10 minutes shorter—pitchers at the plate making for quicker outs than designated hitters).
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In 2004, Major League Baseball declared that its goal was an average game of 2:45.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] By 2014, though, the average MLB game took over three hours to complete.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The lengthening of games is attributed to longer breaks between half-innings for television commercials, increased offense, more pitching changes, and a slower pace of play, with pitchers taking more time between each delivery, and batters stepping out of the box more frequently.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Other leagues have experienced similar issues.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In 2008, Nippon Professional Baseball took steps aimed at shortening games by 12 minutes from the preceding decade's average of 3:18.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In 2016, the average nine-inning playoff game in Major League baseball was 3 hours and 35 minutes.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] This was up 10 minutes from 2015 and 21 minutes from 2014.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In response to the lengthening of the game, MLB decided from the 2023 season onward to institute a pitch clock rule to penalize batters and pitchers who take too much time between pitches; this had the effect of shortening 2023 regular season games by 24 minutes on average.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Although baseball is a team sport, individual players are often placed under scrutiny and pressure.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] While rewarding, it has sometimes been described as "ruthless" due to the pressure on the individual player.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] In 1915, a baseball instructional manual pointed out that every single pitch, of which there are often more than two hundred in a game, involves an individual, one-on-one contest: "the pitcher and the batter in a battle of wits".
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Pitcher, batter, and fielder all act essentially independent of each other.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] While coaching staffs can signal pitcher or batter to pursue certain tactics, the execution of the play itself is a series of solitary acts.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] If the batter hits a line drive, the outfielder is solely responsible for deciding to try to catch it or play it on the bounce and for succeeding or failing.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The statistical precision of baseball is both facilitated by this isolation and reinforces it.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] There is no statistical equivalent in cricket for the fielding error and thus less emphasis on personal responsibility in this area of play.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Unlike those of most sports, baseball playing fields can vary significantly in size and shape.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Major league teams often skirt even this rule.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] For example, at Daikin Park, which became the home of the Houston Astros in 2000, the Crawford Boxes in left field are only 315 feet (96 m) from home plate.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] There are no rules at all that address the height of fences or other structures at the edge of the outfield.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The most famously idiosyncratic outfield boundary is the left-field wall at Boston's Fenway Park, in use since 1912: the Green Monster is 310 feet (94 m) from home plate down the line and 37 feet (11 m) tall.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Similarly, there are no regulations at all concerning the dimensions of foul territory.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Thus a foul fly ball may be entirely out of play in a park with little space between the foul lines and the stands, but a foulout in a park with more expansive foul ground.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] A fence in foul territory that is close to the outfield line will tend to direct balls that strike it back toward the fielders, while one that is farther away may actually prompt more collisions, as outfielders run full speed to field balls deep in the corner.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] These variations can make the difference between a double and a triple or inside-the-park home run.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The surface of the field is also unregulated.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] While the adjacent image shows a traditional field surfacing arrangement (and the one used by virtually all MLB teams with naturally surfaced fields), teams are free to decide what areas will be grassed or bare.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Some fields—including several in MLB—use artificial turf.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Surface variations can have a significant effect on how ground balls behave and are fielded as well as on baserunning.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Similarly, the presence of a roof (seven major league teams play in stadiums with permanent or retractable roofs) can greatly affect how fly balls are played.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] While football and soccer players deal with similar variations of field surface and stadium covering, the size and shape of their fields are much more standardized.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The area out-of-bounds on a football or soccer field does not affect play the way foul territory in baseball does, so variations in that regard are largely insignificant.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] These physical variations create a distinctive set of playing conditions at each ballpark.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Other local factors, such as altitude and climate, can also significantly affect play.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] A given stadium may acquire a reputation as a pitcher's park or a hitter's park, if one or the other discipline notably benefits from its unique mix of elements.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The most exceptional park in this regard is Coors Field, home of the Colorado Rockies.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Its high altitude—5,282 feet (1,610 m) above sea level—is partly responsible for giving it the strongest hitter's park effect in the major leagues due to the low air pressure.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] Wrigley Field, home of the Chicago Cubs, is known for its fickle disposition: a pitcher's park when the strong winds off Lake Michigan are blowing in, it becomes more of a hitter's park when they are blowing out.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] The absence of a standardized field affects not only how particular games play out, but the nature of team rosters and players' statistical records.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] For example, hitting a fly ball 330 feet (100 m) into right field might result in an easy catch on the warning track at one park, and a home run at another.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] A team that plays in a park with a relatively short right field, such as the New York Yankees, will tend to stock its roster with left-handed pull hitters, who can best exploit it.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p01] On the individual level, a player who spends most of his career with a team that plays in a hitter's park will gain an advantage in batting statistics over time—even more so if his talents are especially suited to the park.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] Organized baseball lends itself to statistics to a greater degree than many other sports.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] Each play is discrete and has a relatively small number of possible outcomes.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] The Official Baseball Rules administered by MLB require the official scorer to categorize each baseball play unambiguously.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] The rules provide detailed criteria to promote consistency.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] The score report is the official basis for both the box score of the game and the relevant statistical records.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] General managers, managers, and baseball scouts use statistics to evaluate players and make strategic decisions.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] Certain traditional statistics are familiar to most baseball fans.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] Among the many other statistics that are kept are those collectively known as *situational statistics*.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] For example, statistics can indicate which specific pitchers a certain batter performs best against.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] If a given situation statistically favors a certain batter, the manager of the fielding team may be more likely to change pitchers or have the pitcher intentionally walk the batter in order to face one who is less likely to succeed.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] Sabermetrics is the field of baseball statistical study and the development of new statistics and analytical tools.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] Such new statistics are also called sabermetrics.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] The term was coined around 1980 by one of the field's leading proponents, Bill James, and derives from the Society for American Baseball Research (SABR).
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] Writing in 1919, philosopher Morris Raphael Cohen described baseball as the national religion of the US.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] In the words of sports columnist Jayson Stark, baseball has long been "a unique paragon of American culture"—a status he sees as devastated by the steroid abuse scandal.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] American influence in the Western Hemisphere has meant that baseball grew significantly in the region.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] A century later, the situation was very different.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] With the rise in popularity of other team sports with much higher average ticket prices—football, basketball, and hockey—professional baseball had become among the most popular blue-collar-oriented American spectator sports.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] Overall, baseball has a large following in the United States; a 2006 poll found that nearly half of Americans are fans.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] This led to baseball being granted the title of "America's favorite pastime" by many American baseball fans.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] As historians and scholars now speculate, baseball is a metaphor of the American way of life In the late 1900s and early 2000s, baseball's position compared to football in the United States moved in contradictory directions.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] In 2008, MLB set a revenue record of $6.5 billion, matching the NFL's revenue for the first time in decades.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] A new MLB revenue record of more than $10 billion was set in 2017.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] On the other hand, the percentage of American sports fans polled who named baseball as their favorite sport was 9%, compared to pro football at 37%.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] In 1985, the respective figures were pro football 24%, baseball 23%.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] Because there are so many more major league games played, there is no comparison in overall attendance.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] In 2008, total attendance at major league games was the second-highest in history: 78.6 million, 0.7% off the record set the previous year.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] The following year, amid the U.S. recession, attendance fell by 6.6% to 73.4 million.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] Eight years later, it dropped under 73 million.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] Attendance at games held under the Minor League Baseball umbrella set a record in 2008, with 43.3 million.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] While MLB games have not drawn the same national TV viewership as football games, MLB games are dominant in teams' local markets and regularly lead all programs in primetime in their markets during the summer.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] After multiple years of declines since 2017, baseball attendance has grown slightly in recent years.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] In 2024, attendance was 71.3 million, the highest since 2017.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] Baseball is very popular in Venezuela; in 2011, 95% of people surveyed claimed it to be the national sport.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] In Nicaragua and Panama, baseball is also considered the national sport.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] While soccer is still more popular, baseball is a fast-growing sport in Mexico.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] In 2024, top Mexican League baseball teams outdraw some Liga MX teams in attendance.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] Baseball also is somewhat popular in Colombia, though secondary to soccer, especially in coastal areas such as Barranquilla and Cartagena which are near the Caribbean.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] In recent years, baseball has grown in popularity in Colombia, especially in the capital of Bogotá, due an increase of Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] In Brazil, baseball fan popularity has grown in the last few years, thanks to MLB broadcasts in Brazilian ESPN and the historic silver medal in 2023 Pan-American games.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] However, it still lags behind basketball and American football in the list of most played sports in Brazil.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] Baseball has also grown in popularity in Argentina and Peru in recent years due to Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] Costa Rica has also seen a growth in the popularity of baseball.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] Since 1987, baseballs have exclusively been made in the Costa Rican town of Turrialba.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] In recent years, Major leaguer Mauricio Dubón has made efforts to increase support for the sport in the country.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] The sport's overall popularity in Latin America has assisted in integrating Latin American migrants to the United States.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] Since the early 1980s, the Dominican Republic, in particular the city of San Pedro de Macorís, has been the major leagues' primary source of foreign talent.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] In 2017, 83 of the 868 players on MLB Opening Day rosters (and disabled lists) were from the country.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] Among other Caribbean countries and territories, a combined 97 MLB players were born in Venezuela, Cuba, and Puerto Rico.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] Hall-of-Famer Roberto Clemente remains one of the greatest national heroes in Puerto Rico's history.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] While baseball has long been the island's primary athletic pastime, its once well-attended professional winter league has declined in popularity since 1990, when young Puerto Rican players began to be included in the major leagues' annual first-year player draft.
[src:clutch-hitter/baseball-p02] In Cuba, where baseball is by every reckoning the national sport, the national team overshadows the city and provincial teams that play in the top-level domestic leagues.
